<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Bari     12-01 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Bari,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lynn Bari, Sultry Screen Siren of '30s, '40s, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLETA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lynn Bari, an actress who appeared in
dozens of low-budget Hollywood films during the Depression years,
has died.
   Miss Bari died Nov. 20 at Goleta Valley Community Hospital,
Daily Variety reported Thursday. The cause of death was listed as
cardiac failure.
   Hospital officials said she listed her age as 69, but film
anthologies show she was born in either 1913 or 1915.
   The husky-voiced siren appeared in nearly 50 movies, mostly in
the '30s and '40s. Her credits include ``Dancing Lady,'' in which
Fred Astaire made his screen debut, ``Sun Valley Serenada'' and
``Orchestra Wives.'' She also had a role in ``The Bridge of San
Luis Rey.''
   Miss Bari made her final picture, ``The Young Runaways,'' in
1968. She also appeared in two short-lived television series in the
50s, ``Detective's Wife'' and ``Boss Lady.''
   She was born Marjorie Fisher in Roanoke, Va.
   The actress retired to the Santa Barbara area to be near her
son, John, who was the object of a stormy custody fight between
Miss Bari and her second husband, Sid Luft, who later married Judy
Garland.
   Her first husband was Walter Kane, an agent, and her third was
Dr. Nathan Rickles, a Beverly Hills psychiatrist. They divorced in
1972 after 17 years of marriage.
   Her ashes were scattered at sea, Daily Variety said.
</TEXT>
