<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-Banker 1stLd-Writethru   12-01 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Banker, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0487,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massive Search Launched for Killers of Banker</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with prosecutor saying attack planned
weeks in advance, EDITS to tighten. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAD HOMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terrorists meticulously planned
for weeks the bomb attack that killed one of the world's most
powerful financiers, the chief federal prosecutor said today.
   Police searched nationwide for a 31-year-old terrorist suspect
wanted in the killing of Alfred Herrhausen, the head of Deutsche
Bank. He was slain when a bomb ripped through his car Thursday in
the Frankfurt suburb of Bad Homburg.
   In Frankfurt, 5,000 people took part in a silent march past
Deutsche Bank headquarters in memory of Herrhausen.
   Authorities have offered a $2.2 million reward for the capture
of Herrhausen's killers.
   Herrhausen, 59, headed the country's largest bank and had been
one of the world's most influential financial figures.
   The Red Army Faction, which had been relatively dormant for
three years, claimed responsibility for the sophisticated bomb
attack that wrecked Herrhausen's armored car as he was being driven
through this affluent suburb to work in nearby Frankfurt.
   Herrhausen's driver survived the attack with serious injuries.
   ``The perpetrators began preparing for the attack at least four
or five weeks ago,'' said chief federal prosecutor Kurt Rebmann.
   ``Near the area of the attack wires had been buried in the
asphalt. The asphalt had been chiseled out up to nearby bushes, and
after the wires were laid filled in again,'' he said.
   Rebmann said the terrorists took care to tint new asphalt poured
over the wires the same as the rest of the 4-foot-wide sidewalk to
make the work unnoticable.
   His office said one of two men seen running from the scene
matched the description of 31-year-old Christoph Seidler.
   A Hamburg court in 1981 convicted Seidler of supporting the
leftist Red Army Faction, which claimed responsibility for the bomb
attack.
   Seidler has been a fugitive for several years. His name
routinely appears on a wanted poster of two dozen leftist
terrorists that is displayed in West German post offices and other
public places, said prosecutor's spokesman Hans-Juergen Foerster.
   Seidler has been involved with the Red Army Faction for at least
a decade, said a statement issued by Rebmann's office.
   It said Seidler also was sought in a bank robbery in 1985.
   A controversy developed over whether Herrhausen had been given
enough protection. Media reports said authorities had received
indications he might have been singled out as the target of a
possible attack.
   Imprisoned Red Army Faction members went on a hunger strike
earlier this year to back demands to be housed together in one
prison.
   They broke off their hunger strike without gaining the
concession but issued a statement warning about new steps in their
``anti-imperialist struggle.''
   The Red Army Faction has a long history of attacks against West
German business and political figures, as well as against U.S.
military targets.
   The group had been little heard of since the 1986 murders of
Karl Heinz Beckurts, chairman of the giant Siemens industrial
concern, and diplomat Gerold von Braunmuehl. However, the group was
believed to be involved in an unsuccessful attempt on the life of
finance ministry official Hans Tietmeyer in September 1988.
   Rebmann said authorities would have to review security measures
because of the sophistication of the device that killed Herrhausen.
   Foerster said the explosive appeared to have been attached to a
bicycle placed on the street.
   He said the bomb was detonated by a sophisticated light-beam
device that had never been used before in a terrorist attack in
West Germany. Herrhausen's car triggered the explosion by passing
through the light beam, he said.
   ``For a long time, the Deutsche Bank and Herrhausen in
particular have been targeted by the Red Army Faction,'' Foerster
said.
   The spokesman noted that leftist terrorists for years had
accused Deutsche Bank of ``repression'' and of fueling the
``military-industrial'' complex with the bank's worldwide
investments.
   Herrhausen had been a friend and an adviser of Chancellor Helmut
Kohl, often accompanying the chancellor on major foreign trips.
   The tall, striking bank chief had been leading the Deutsche Bank
on an aggressive expansion course aimed at making the institution
one of the top 10 or 15 banks in the world.
   Herrhausen also urged greater investment in the Soviet Union and
other parts of Eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
