<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Medfly     12-01 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medfly,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medfly Scare Spreads to Orange County</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BREA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Helicopters dumped pesticide on a
10-square-mile area radiating from a guava tree where a pregnant
Medfly was trapped, marking the first 1989 infestation in
citrus-rich Orange County.
   Residents covered cars, fish ponds, and bird baths with plastic
tarps to protect them from the gooey pesticide malathion Thursday
night before two helicopters began spraying in the latest attack on
the Mediterranean fruit fly.
   The malathion is mixed into a sweet bait mixture that contains
corn syrup and can ruin car finishes.
   The spraying in Brea and neighboring La Habra Heights came as
agricultural officials announced expansion of two malathion
spraying zones centered around Monrovia, just east of Los Angeles,
and Downey, to the southeast. The spraying on those two areas is
scheduled for next week.
   The western section of this city about 20 miles southeast of
downtown Los Angeles that underwent spraying once was home to
orange groves and strawberry fields, but has become a developed
suburb with homes and a regional shopping center.
   ``Nobody likes the idea, but everyone recognizes the need to do
it,'' Mayor Gene Leyton said before the spraying began.
   Los Angeles County Agricultural Commission chief deputy Bill
Edwards said Thursday an area set for spraying next week was
expanded to 21 square miles after a Medfly was found in a trap set
in suburban Temple City.
   The prolific Medfly lays its eggs in 250 kinds of fruits and
vegetables, making it a serious threat to the state's $16 billion
farm economy.
   Los Angeles County's agriculture business is minimal, but Orange
County still has a $225 million annual business, including such
Medfly targets as citrus fruit, avocados and strawberries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
