<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1054EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-SummitRdp 13thLd-Writethru a0573 12-01 1204</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit Rdp, 13th Ld-Writethru, a0573,1,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Arrives for Malta Summit; Gorbachev Meets Pope</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS three grafs after pvs 8th graf bgng, Bush saluted, to
update with Bush tour of carrier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSAXLOKK BAY, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush warmly praised
Mikhail S. Gorbachev today and said he hoped their weekend summit
would lead to a freedom that ``will last for generations.'' The
Soviet leader met with Pope John Paul II at the Vatican and pledged
religious liberty throughout his communist homeland.
   Bush arrived at the blustery summit site after ordering American
warplanes to support Philippines President Corazon Aquino's
struggle against a military coup attempt.
   While Gorbachev promised to establish diplomatic ties with the
Vatican and guarantee religious freedom for all Soviet citizens,
one of his major European allies _ East Germany _ took another
major step toward democratic reform.
   Touring the U.S. aircraft carrier Forrestal in the Mediterranean
after his arrival for the weekend summit, Bush said he yearned for
a future ``free of both tyranny and fear,'' and urged the Soviet
Union to ``join us in building that kind of future.''
   ``A new freedom is sweeping the globe,'' the president told
officers and crew members aboard the carrier before arriving at the
USS Belknap, his home for the next two days. ``Our meeting here off
Malta will last a few days, but the freedom we seek will last for
generations.''
   Bush presented the Forrestal's crew with a piece of the
crumbling Berlin Wall as ``a symbol of the peace we seek.'' He
thanked them for making the Malta summit possible because ``you and
sailors like you around the world have kept us strong.''
   He said the two-day summit starting Saturday aboard U.S. and
Soviet warships anchored in the harbor off Malta's shore presented
``a historic opportunity to foster the peace.''
   Bush saluted Gorbachev as ``a dynamic new Soviet leader willing,
as Lincoln said, to think anew.'' The president added that ``we
want him to succeed'' in bring economic and political reforms to
the Soviet Union.
   On the carrier, Bush watched as warplanes were catapulated off
the deck, screeching into the sky on maneuvers. ``I've got a banana
in my ear,'' he joked to reporters, referring to yellow earplugs he
wore during the noisy demonstration.
   A F-14 surprised the president with a thunderous sonic boom, and
Bush ducked partially down behind a railing, as did other visitors.
Quickly recovering, the president grinned and screwed up his face
in mock horror for the cameras.
   Bush also joined enlisted men in the mess for a lunch of lasagna
and a glass of milk.
   After the 70-minute Vatican meeting, Gorbachev said the Soviet
Union would soon adopt a law guaranteeing religious freedom within
its borders, and would establish diplomatic ties with the Vatican.
   ``People of many confessions, including Christians, Moslems,
Jews, Buddhists and others live in the Soviet Union,'' Gorbachev
said. ``All of them have a right to satisfy their spiritual needs.''
   The pope called the meeting, the first between a Soviet leader
and the head of the Roman Catholic Church, a ``promise-filled sign
for the future,'' and pledged support for Gorbachev's attempt to
reform Soviet society.
   A top Soviet official, meanwhile, said he doubted any formal
agreements would be signed during the summit.
   ``I think President Bush is right when he says there will be no
concrete agreement signed during the actual meeting,'' said
Valentin Falin, the head of the International Department of the
Soviet Communist Party.
   But Falin, an architect of Soviet policy toward Europe, hinted
that Gorbachev will try to nudge Bush toward accords on banning
nuclear weapons from the Mediterranean Sea and coping with
political changes sweeping Eastern Europe.
   After his arrival, Bush spent the day visiting officers and crew
members aboard the U.S. aircraft carrier Forrestal in the
Mediterranean and dealing with a violent military insurrection
against the Aquino government in Manila.
   En route to Malta, Bush ordered U.S. warplanes to provide air
support for the Aquino government against military insurgents who
bombed the presidential palace in Manila.
   ``It is fair to say that the situation is serious,'' Secretary
of State James A. Baker III said. ``We are hopeful the matter will
be contained,'' the president said.
   U.S. officials said American warplanes were circling two air
bases controlled by rebel forces at Villamor and Sangley Point, and
100 American Marines were shifted to Manila to protect the U.S.
Embassy. A Soviet spokesman in Malta denounced the U.S. move as
``interference in internal developments.''
   At the Vatican, Gorbachev broke into a smile as the Polish-born
pontiff offered his hand and guided the Soviet president into the
papal library for private talks at an oaken desk beneath a
religious painting.
   In a major gesture to the Vatican, Soviet officials cleared the
way for legalizing the Ukrainian Catholic Church, which has been
banned since the days of dictator Josef Stalin. An official of the
Soviet republic said today the church's estimated 4 million members
will be allowed to register with Ukrainian authorities like members
of other faiths.
   At the same time, the East German parliament voted
overwhelmingly to change the constitution and eliminate the
Communist Party's guaranteed monopoly on political power, a major
reform demanded by the mass movement for democratic change.
   Gorbachev flies to Malta tonight after meeting with Italian
Premier Giulio Andreotti and business leaders in Milan, Italy.
   Preceding Gorbachev to Malta, Soviet spokesman Gennady Gerasimov
said it was unlikely the summit leaders could do anything to
resolve the conflict in Central America, where the United States
says Soviet arms are continuing to flow to leftist guerrillas.
   ``We are not helping anybody there,'' Gerasimov said during a
``CBS This Morning'' interview. ``It's very dangerous to infuse
great-power rivalry into this conflict, which we think must be
settled by political means.''
   Before boarding Air Force One on Thursday for the summit site,
Bush said the people of Europe can see that ``Mr. Gorbachev and I _
East and West _ are not in some kind of competition. Rather, we're
both working to make the world a more peaceful one.''
   Gorbachev declared Thursday there was no turning back from the
democratic reforms sweeping through the Eastern bloc.
   The Soviet leader said the United States, Canada and European
nations should hold a ``Helsinki 2'' meeting earlier than the 1992
date set under the 1975 Helsinki Accords on human rights and
security in Europe.
   Bush, asked by reporters aboard Air Force One about Gorbachev's
proposal, said: ``I'll talk to him. Any ideas he's got, I'll
discuss them with him. Then we'll let you know.''
   Malta's entire 1,200-man army was mobilized to assist in
ensuring security for the superpower leaders. Soviet, American and
Maltese flags fluttered side by side throughout the capital city.
   The U.S. and Soviet warships where two days of summit talks will
begin Saturday _ the USS Belknap and the Slava _ were anchored
offshore, visible from the cliffs overlooking the bay.
   Besides the whirlwind changes in Eastern Europe, the 11{ hours
of talks between Bush and Gorbachev are likely to deal with
negotiations to cut nuclear arms and conventional forces, trade
issues, and regional disputes, including a U.S. complaint about
Soviet-made weapons shipped to El Salvador.
</TEXT>
