<FIRST>r a PM-TropicalWeather     12-01 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tropical Weather,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Late-Season Tropical Storm Brings Heavy Rain to Cuba</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical storm warnings went up again in Cuba today
as forecasters watched Karen, a rare late-season tropical storm,
loop southward in the Caribbean after dumping heavy rains on the
island.
   At 11 a.m. EST, the storm was near latitude 19.0 north,
longitude 83.2 west, about 130 miles west of Grand Cayman Island
and about 300 miles south of Havana, said forecasters at the
National Hurricane Center in suburban Coral Gables.
   Karen's highest sustained winds were 40 mph. The storm was
drifting south at 5 mph after a Thursday encounter with a cold
front and was expected to slow to a halt today.
   Storm warnings were posted for western and central Cuba and the
Isle of Youth.
   Forecaster Miles Lawrence said satellite pictures showed an area
of thunderstorms over the system's center. ``That could indicate
temporary strengthening,'' he said. ``It was not really expected.''
   The system surprised forecasters by achieving tropical storm
strength Thursday when its winds hit 39 mph.
   Many communities in South Florida had hoped the storm would help
ease a near-record water shortage, which has led to mandatory water
restrictions in some areas.
   But it seemed Cuba and its coastal waters would get most of the
storm's rains, Lawrence said.
   The hurricane center reported more than 14 inches of rain fell
on Punta del Este on the Isle of Youth Thursday. More than 7 inches
in Matanzas and nearly 5 inches in Havana.
   The hurricane season begins June 1 and ends Nov. 30. However,
hurricanes have been recorded in every month but April.
</TEXT>
