<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary-Defector     12-01 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary-Defector,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarian Government Denies it Expelled Renegade CIA Agent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today denied a report
that it expelled a renegade CIA agent who has been sought by the
United States since his defection to the Soviet Union in 1985.
   The Los Angeles Times quoted a U.S. government source as saying
Hungary revoked Edward Lee Howard's asylum status at least a month
ago, despite protests from the KGB, the Soviet intelligence service.
   But Col. Karoly Nagy, head of the Hungarian Interior Ministry's
Department for the Supervision of Foreign Nationals, told The
Associated Press today that Howard had not been expelled from
Hungary.
   ``As far as I know he is still here, but he has indicated that
he plans to leave Hungary,'' said Nagy. ``He cited personal, family
reasons, nothing political. When he leaves, it will be of his own
free will.''
   When asked about Howard's travel documents, Nagy said, ``I think
he has his American passport. If he has a multiple-entry visa, he
can come and go.''
   The U.S. Embassy said today it had no immediate information on
Howard's reported expulsion.
   Nagy said he did not know where Howard would go if he left
Hungary.
   Howard, who reportedly provided the Soviets with CIA
information, has spent significant periods of time in Hungary since
defecting to Moscow in 1985, according to David Wise, author of a
book on Howard's defection.
   The Los Angeles Times said Howard's wife Mary, who lives in St.
Paul, Minn., had spent up to three months with him in Hungary.
   In its story Thursday, the newspaper quoted a U.S. official as
saying that federal authorities had been trying to persuade Hungary
to expel Howard for months. It did not identify the official.
   CIA Director William H. Webster made a veiled reference to an
expulsion in a speech Wednesday at the National Press Club in
Washington.
   He was asked about cooperation between intelligence services of
East Bloc countries and the Soviets in light of the recent
democratic reforms sweeping Hungary, Poland, East Germany and
Czechoslovakia.
   Webster cited the case of ``a prominent defector from the United
States (who) was permanently expelled from a bloc country which had
provided him comfort and sanctuary in the past. And that would have
been contrary to the wishes of the KGB.''
   Soviet Embassy spokesman Sergei Semyonov said Thursday of
Howard, ``I regret but we know nothing about such a man.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
