<FIRST>u i PM-Pope-Gorbachev 9thLd-Writethru   12-01 1048</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope-Gorbachev, 9th Ld-Writethru,a0586,1076</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Says Soviets Will Guarantee Religious Freedom</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 17 grafs to UPDATE with background on previous attempts
by pope to visit Soviet Union, EDITS to tighten. Pickup 15th graf pvs,
`The Polish-born...' DELETES 22nd graf pvs to conform.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY5,ROM1,3,6</HEAD>
<HEAD>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev pledged in a historic
meeting with Pope John Paul II today that the Soviet Union will
guarantee freedom of religion at home and establish diplomatic ties
with the Vatican.
   Joaquin Navarro, a Vatican spokesman, said Gorbachev also
invited the pope to visit the Soviet Union and that John Paul
thanked him and expressed the hope that developments would allow
him to make the trip.
   After the Vatican meeting, Gorbachev flew to Milan to meet with
business leaders before heading to Malta and summit talks with
President Bush.
   The beaming pope welcomed today's visit _ the first between a
Kremlin chief and Roman Catholic pontiff _ as a ``promise-filled
sign for the future'' and pledged support for Gorbachev's attempt
to reform Soviet society.
   In his address after about 70 minutes of private talks, John
Paul referred to the ``painful trials'' that Soviet believers
suffered in past decades.
   He issued a strong call for religious freedom for all believers
that included a reference to the Ukrainian Catholic Church, which
had been suppressed by Soviet dictator Josef Stalin.
   ``On their behalf _ whether they be of the Latin, Byzantine or
Armenian Rite _ I express the fervent hope that they be able to
practice freely their religious life,'' the pope said.
   The Vatican said the pope in his private talks also raised the
issue of the Ukrainians. In the Soviet Union, officials said they
had cleared the way for the eventual legalization of the Ukrainian
Church.
   In a cautious response to the Vatican meeting, Rome-based
Ukrainian Catholic leader Cardinal Myroslav Lubachivsky restated
the church's demands for full freedom and offered to cooperate with
the rival Russian Orthodox Church.
   The pope also said the Holy See was following with interest
Gorbachev's efforts to renew society and promised support for
``every initiative'' to protect the rights of people and help
ensure peace.
   John Paul spoke first at the news conference, beginning in
Russian and switching to Italian, and Gorbachev responded to the
pope's concerns in his brief remarks.
   ``People of many confessions, including Christians, Moslems,
Jews, Buddhists and others live in the Soviet Union. All of them
have a right to satisfy their spiritual needs,'' Gorbachev said,
speaking in Russian.
   He said a freedom of conscience law would soon be adopted.
   The Soviet leader also said the Vatican and Moscow had reached
agreement in principle to give ``official status to our interstate
relations'' with the details to be worked out by diplomats. The
pope has long sought to re-establish relations with the Soviets,
broken since the Russian Revolution.
   Departing from his prepared text, Gorbachev said: ``We discussed
a future papal visit.'' John Paul has frequently express the wish
to visit the Soviet Union, provided he can meet with his flock all
over the country, including Lithuania and the Ukraine.
   The pope has disclosed on two occasions that he had been barred
from visiting Lithuania, the Roman Catholic stronghold in the
Soviet Union.
   Navarro did not provide a date for such a trip. ``I don't know
when, but certainly the pope will be going some day,'' Navarro told
reporters.
   The Polish-born pontiff, smiling and touching his pectoral
cross, welcomed Gorbachev to the first meeting ever between a
Kremlin chief and pope.
   Gorbachev, the leader of a system that has reviled religion for
most of this century, appeared serious as he walked through the
marble and frescoed halls of the Apostolic Palace but smiled when
the pope offered his hand.
   The two men chatted and posed for photographers before the
white-robed John Paul led Gorbachev, wearing a pin-striped suit,
into the papal library, guiding him to an oak desk beneath a
religious painting to begin the closed-door talks.
   In their private meeting, the two men spoke alone in Russian for
five minutes. Then their interpreters joined them for the rest of
the session and John Paul switched to Polish.
   As Gorbachev and his wife, Raisa, entered the Apostolic Palace,
they were greeted by bemedaled Vatican dignitaries and received a
salute from a detachment of Swiss Guards, the pope's ceremonial
army.
   Mrs. Gorbachev's red dress raised eyebrows at the Vatican, where
protocol normally calls for women to wear dark dresses. But she
seemed at ease as she toured the palace and asked questions about
its art works.
   The pope and Gorbachev smiled as Mrs. Gorbachev and the Soviet
entourage were ushered into the library after the talks.
   Earlier in the clear but chilly morning, thousands of Romans
lined the broad avenue leading to St. Peter's basilica, the largest
church in Christendom, and cheered as Gorbachev's black limousine
headed into St. Peter's Square and he entered the Vatican.
   In announcing that the Ukrainian Church will be legalized,
Nikolai Kolesnik of the Soviet republic's Council on Religious
Affairs said from Kiev that regional officials have decided that
``societies of Greek (rite) Catholics can be registered like other
religious groups'' as now required by Soviet law.
   The church was forcibly merged under dictator Josef Stalin with
the Russian Orthodox Church in 1946 and went underground. According
to Western sources, it has up to 4 million members.
   Kolesnik said in a telephone interview from Kiev to The
Associated Press in Moscow that it was possible the Ukrainian
Catholic church's hierarchy could also be restored.
   Gorbachev would like Vatican support for his reform policies,
and was believed to be seeking a pledge from John Paul that he
would use his influence to keep the church from becoming a vehicle
for nationalism in the Baltic republics and the Ukraine.
   John Paul, a strong anti-Communist, indicated from the outset of
his papacy 11 years ago that he intended to battle for the rights
of his fellow Eastern Europeans. His return to Poland in 1979
sparked calls for democratic reforms that led to the birth of the
Solidarity labor movement.
   The Turkish gunman who shot John Paul in May 1981 claimed he had
Bulgarian and Soviet support, although the allegations were never
proved.
</TEXT>
