<FIRST>u a PM-Flight103 2ndLd-Writethru a0565 12-01 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0565,0773</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Palestinian Leader Recruited Terrorists to Bomb Flight 103</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-8 bgng `Scottish investigators...' with 3 grafs
to UPDATE with court hearing in Sweden. Picks up 9th graf, `ABC said...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three terrorists recruited by Palestinian
guerrilla leader Ahmed Jibril built the bomb that destroyed Pan Am
Flight 103 and killed 270 people, ABC-TV reported.
   The three, identified as Ibrahim Twafik-Youssef, Mohammed
al-Makoussi and Hassan Hadi al-Ahar, had been imprisoned by Israel
for nine years for a failed rocket attack on an El Al jet at
Nairobi Airport in 1976, ABC said Thursday on its ``PrimeTime
Live'' program. The network cited terrorist sources.
   ABC reported that Jibril, a former Syrian army captain who heads
the Syrian-backed Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine-General Command, has bragged privately that he was behind
the bombing and was paid by Iran.
   Terrorism experts and media investigations previously suspected
Jibril in the case. Some theories hold that Iran hired the
organization to avenge a U.S. warship's downing in July 1988 of an
Iran Air jet with 290 people aboard. Iran has denied any
involvement.
   But Jibril publicly has denied any involvement with the
explosion of Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, on Dec. 21, 1988.
All 259 people aboard the Boeing 747 and 11 on the ground were
killed.
   Authorities asked a court in Sweden today to approve the seizure
of 15 bags of clothing by Scottish detectives from the apartment of
a Palestinian suspected of complicity in the bombing.
   The lawyer for Mohammed Abo Talb, who is awaiting a verdict on
separate charges related to terrorist bombings in Scandinavia and
Holland, asked the court to have the clothing returned. The judge
said he would decide by Monday.
   Abo Talb, a former activist in the Palestine Popular Struggle
Front, was linked to Flight 103 when it was established he was in
Malta two months before the plane explosion.
   ABC said Scottish police raided Abo Talb's apartment in Upsalla,
Sweden, three days ago and found clothes that matched those found
in the suitcase believed to have contained the bomb that exploded
on Flight 103.
   A government source told The Associated Press on Tuesday that
clothing fragments from the exploded suitcase had been traced to a
store on the Mediterranean island of Malta.
   ABC reported that on Oct. 23, 1988, Abo Talb went to a store
called Mary's House on Malta and bought clothes chosen at random.
Court records examined in Sweden by the AP confirm that Abo Talb
visited Malta Oct. 19-26, 1988, after spending a day in Cyprus.
   British newspapers had previously reported on the Malta clothing
link.
   Investigators believe they have linked Abo Talb to Jibril, ABC
said.
   Previously, the Sunday Times of London said Jibril ordered his
top aide, Hafez Dalkamoni, to set up the bombing team, and that
Dalkamoni recruited Marwan Khreesat, a Jordanian member of the
Popular Front, whom the Sunday Times and others had named as the
bombmaker.
   ABC said Jibril did set up an operation involving Dalkamoni and
Khreesat, but it was a smokescreen to divert attention from his
real plan to bring down a U.S. airliner. ABC added that Jibril
suspected Khreesat of being a spy.
   Khreesat and Dalkamoni were arrested in West Germany two months
before the Pan Am bombing during raids of people suspected of
planning a terrorist attack there. Raids in Frankfurt and Nuess
also yielded Semtex bombs with air pressure-sensitive detonators,
like the one that later blew up Flight 103.
   Dalkamoni and another Palestinian remain in a West German jail;
the others were released. The British Broadcasting Co. has reported
that Khreesat was freed because he was a double agent working
inside the Popular Front for Jordanian intelligence, and now lives
in Jordan.
   The network said Jibril has bragged privately that Iran paid him
$10 million for the bombing. In May, the West German magazine Quick
reported that Iran paid Jibril $1.3 million to carry out the attack.
   London's Sunday Times has reported that a baggage list shows one
suitcae was transferred onto the Pan Am flight in Frankfurt, West
Germany, from Air Malta Flight KM180. In violation of international
regulations, it was not accompanied by a passenger. Air Malta has
said all the flight's passengers and baggage were accounted for.
   The Pan Am plane flew to London, where it became Flight 103. It
exploded en route to New York City.
   West German police have maintained there is insufficient proof
that the bomb was put on board in Frankfurt.
</TEXT>
