<SECOND>PM-School Hostage, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0591,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Shoots Wife, Rapes Two Teachers in Kindergarten Classroom</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT woman's name to Adria, based on interview
with woman, sted Andrea, spelling provided by police. Note contents.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NATCHEZ, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man shot his estranged wife and raped
two teachers in front of 19 children in a school standoff with
police that ended when a teacher grabbed the weapon from the man,
authorities said.
   Larry Bates, 35, was charged with aggravated assault, two counts
of capital rape, two counts of sexual battery, possession of a
firearm by a felon and 22 counts of kidnapping in the incident
Thursday at Northside Primary School, said Natchez Police Chief
Eddie Jones.
   Adria Bates, 40, a teacher's aide at the school, suffered
gunshot wounds to the scalp and back. She was in good condition
today at Jefferson Davis Memorial Hospital, a nursing supervisor
said.
   Mrs. Bates said she recently had filed for divorce and that
Bates had ``been hearing a lot of untrue rumors.'' She did not
elaborate.
   ``It was humiliating to the children and to the other staff,''
she said from her hospital bed.
   The two teachers who were raped and beaten were treated at the
hospital and released.
   Police and sheriff's deputies stormed the kindergarten classroom
to end the hourlong standoff after a teacher grabbed a .38-caliber
revolver from Bates, Assistant Police Chief George Rutherford said.
   ``A tragic situation was prevented with only one ... injury due
to the quick wits of the teachers involved,'' said Adams County
Sheriff Tommy Ferrell. ``These were pretty gutsy women that could
do something of that sort.''
   Rutherford said police received a report of a man on the campus
about 1:30 p.m.
   Officials quoted witnesses as saying Bates shot at his wife's
head.
   Two shots were fired in the classroom, police said, but it was
not certain whether both struck her or whether her injures were
caused by a ricocheting bullet.
   Rutherford said Bates lined the 5- and 6-year-old children in
front of windows _ between himself and police _ and had the
teachers cover the glass with paper.
   There were four teachers and aides in the classroom when the
incident began, Rutherford said, but Bates sent one for aspirin and
had his wounded wife removed from the room.
   Officers said the man ordered the children to look away while he
sexually assaulted the two teachers.
   Rutherford said Jones talked to Bates on the school's intercom
system and ``distracted him long enough for one of the teachers to
grab the weapon.''
   Bates, who had previously been convicted of burglary and
assault, was taken to the Adams County Jail.
</TEXT>
