<HEAD>Stolen Asian Art Recovered, Man Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Asian artwork worth $1 million that was
stolen from a New York collector on Christmas Day 11 years ago was
recovered with the help of an art-theft sleuth, police said.
   About 300 Tibetan and Nepalese items, including ``Buddhas and
all different kinds of brass and prayer wheels,'' were found at a
residence where police arrested Craig K. Warner, 40, police Lt.
Buster Althizer said Thursday.
   The artwork was one of the biggest collections of its type and
had an estimated value of $1 million, he said.
   Detective Bill Martin, who specializes in art theft, tracked the
stolen artworks during a four-month investigation, Althizer said.
   ``He received a letter from the owner who had been looking for
the art for some time,'' Althizer said. ``Martin was able to
develop a lead and followed up on it.''
   Althizer said the art collector, Dr. Jane Werner of New York
City, planned to fly west to claim her belongings.
   ``She is beside herself'' with happiness at the recovery,
Althizer said.
   Warner, arrested for investigation of receiving stolen property,
was booked into the jail ward at County-USC Medical Center.
Althizer would not disclose the nature of his illness.
</TEXT>
