<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru a0484 12-01 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0484,0794</SECOND>
<HEAD>Capital Calm, but Fighting Reported Nearby</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with calm in capital but fighting
in nearby city; pickup 6th graf pvs, `Leaders of...' DELETES grafs 16-17
pvs to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sporadic fighting between
leftist rebels and government forces was reported outside the
capital today, but San Salvador was calm and some residents used
the lull to repair their damaged homes.
   Others in the capital, fearing more battles in coming weeks,
closed up their homes and headed for refuge with relatives or
abroad.
   Today's calm followed two days of combat that forced the
evacuation of many people from the city's wealthy neighborhoods,
including nearly 300 Americans.
   Elsewhere, assault rifle fire was heard outside Zacatecoluca, a
provincial capital 25 miles southeast of San Salvador, residents
reported. Two O-2 observation planes fired several rockets at
suspected guerrilla positions outside the city of 75,000 people.
   For the first time in the 10-year-old civil war, the guerrillas
reportedly fired a surface-to-air missile on Wednesday, in
Zacatecoluca.
   The SAM-7 fired at a A-37 jet fighter missed its mark, but air
force pilots obviously were worried about the missiles.
Zacatecoloca residents, contacted by telephone, said the O-2s were
flying very low, which makes them harder to hit with the missiles
but easier to hit with rifle fire.
   A total of 282 Americans, many living in two San Salvador
neighborhoods under attack this week, fled the country Thursday
when the guerrillas declared a six-hour truce. U.S. Embassy
personnel and dependents were among those who departed in two
chartered planes.
   The neighborhoods, on the west and southwest side of the city,
were the scene of a surprise rebel incursion late Tuesday and early
Wednesday that turned their stately tree-lined streets and
carefully tended lawns into battle zones.
   Leaders of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front rebel
organization said the invasion was part of the rebel's biggest
offensive in the decade-old war, which was launched Nov. 11.
   Infiltrating in small groups under cover of darkness, the
guerrillas had seized and entrenched themselves in about 40 homes
in the neighborhoods.
   There were no reports of civilian casualties from the fierce
fighting. The number of combatants killed was not known, although
reporters at the time counted 11 bodies in battle gear lying in the
area.
   By nightfall Thursday, when a dusk-to-dawn curfew went into
effect, the rebels vanished as silently as they had come and no
more shooting could be heard.
   But the neighborhoods remained littered with spent cartridges,
burned-out luxury cars, downed power lines, and some damaged homes
and mansions _ and a few rebel dead.
   One of the bodies in Escalon had been burned by soldiers and
dumped, headfirst into a mesh trash can outside a mansion, a crude
cardboard sign scrawled with a skull and crossbones jammed beside
the charred remains.
   Written on the piece of cardboard was a sign in Spanish saying
the soldiers take no prisoners. ``There is no man, no law that
holds us back,'' the sign added.
   One infantryman with a shoulder-length mop of hair lounged by
the trash can. ``He thought he'd scare us,'' the soldier explained
laughing, ``We burned him.''
   Before departing, the rebels set the National Information Center
ablaze.
   The center was set up Nov. 12, when the government suspended
constitutional guarantees, declared a state-of-siege, imposed
censorship on Salvadoran news media and forced the networks to
broadcast its news programs several hours every day.
   President Alfredo Cristiani's rightist government Sunday accused
Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government of smuggling the missiles
and other military supplies to the rebels and suspended diplomatic
relations with the neighboring country.
   Cristani denounced the Sandinistas a day after a two small
planes were caught reportedly ferrying the military hardware.
   He said both planes had taken off from Nicaragua; Nicaragua's
president, Daniel Ortega, did not deny the charge.
   The United States, which has been supporting a succession of
Salvadoran governments with military and economic aid, protested to
the Soviet Union, which had been supplying the Sandinistas
regularly with weapons over the years.
   President Bush said he would also bring up the issue during a
summit meeting he is holding off the coast of Malta with Soviet
President Mikhail Gorbachev.
   More than 71,000 people have been killed, most of them
civilians, since the civil war began Oct. 15, 1979, according to
human rights groups.
   On Thursday, the military searched the homes of two U.S.
free-lance journalists and that of Ricardo Chacon, the Salvadoran
bureau chief of the Spanish news agency ACAN-EFE, and warned news
agencies to be ``objective'' in their reporting.
</TEXT>
