<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Iraq-Martyrs     12-01 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Iraq-Martyrs,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraq Remembers War Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq on Friday marked ``Martyr Day,''
commemorating the deaths of hundreds of thousands of Iraqis who
fell in its war with Iran.
   Special sermons were held in mosques and churches at dawn with
Moslem prayers and pealing bells booming out over loudspeakers.
Official radio and TV pre-empted regular programming to broadcast
dirges and specials on the war.
   Local party officials toured houses of families who lost sons in
the eight-year war to express their condolences.
   Western military experts have said Iran and Iraq suffered about
1 million dead in the war that started in September 1980.
   Iraq decided to commemorate Martyr Day after an Iranian
opposition group reported that extremist Revolutionary Guards once
machine gunned hundreds of Iraqi soldiers taken captive during a
major battle in southern sector of the gulf war. They were reported
killed near the southern Iranian port of Sunsangard on Dec. 1, 1982.
   The Iranians denied the report from the Mujahedeen Khalq, based
in Baghdad.
   The war ended with a United Nations cease-fire August 1988, but
all attempts to establish a formal peace treaty have failed.
