<FIRST>r i AM-Tibet     12-01 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tibet,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tibetan Court Imprisons 10</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten Tibetan members of a pro-independence group,
including at least eight Buddhist monks, were sentenced to prison
terms in the Tibetan capital of Lhasa, official reports said Friday.
   The 10 received sentences Thursday ranging from five to 19 years
for forming a ``counterrevolutionary organization'' in January, the
Xinhua News Agency said.
   At least eight of those convicted were monks from the Drepung
Monastery, a community of more than 400 monks on the outskirts of
Lhasa and one of the centers of Buddhist-led pro-independence
unrest in Lhasa in the past two years.
   The reports said the organization collected information and
mimeographed ``reactionary leaflets for their foreign boss,'' an
apparent reference to Tibet's exiled spiritual leader the Dalai
Lama.
   The Dalai Lama, who has lived in exile in India since fleeing
Tibet after a failed uprising against the Chinese military in 1959,
on Dec. 10 will receive the Nobel Peace Prize for his efforts to
achieve indpendence for his homeland through peaceful means.
   China has strongly objected to the decision to award the Dalai
Lama the prize, saying he has incited reactionary forces trying to
split the nation.
   The Beijing government imposed martial law in Lhasa on March 8
after three days of violent riots, the fourth major outbreak of
anti-Chinese disturbances in the city since the fall of 1987.
   In September, Tibetan courts sentenced 10 men, including at
least six monks, to prison terms of up to life on charges of
rioting and spying for the Dalai Lama during the March uprising.
   Nine nuns were also reportedly sentenced to labor camp in
September for shouting pro-independence slogans at a festival
earlier in the month.
</TEXT>
