<FIRST>r w AM-Boschwitz-Germany     12-01 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boschwitz-Germany,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minnesota Senator Planning Return To Berlin Birthplace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time since his family fled the
Nazis in 1933, Minnesota Sen. Rudy Boschwitz will return to his
native Germany to look for his birthplace in East Berlin.
   Boschwitz, a member of the Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee
on European affairs, will stop in Berlin next spring before going
on to Poland with a group of Minnesota farmers for what an aide
describes as a ``Peace Corps-type'' visit to offer help to the
primitive Polish dairy industry.
   The senator's office did not announce any dates for the trip.
   Boschwitz knows the address of his childhood home, which he
believes to be in East Berlin, but doesn't really remember it since
he was 2 when his Jewish family left Germany, he said Friday.
   ``I've seen a picture of it that is very much different than how
I remember it,'' he said. ``I really don't have any recollection.''
   Boschwitz's parents, left Berlin with him and his sister six
months after Adolf Hitler came to power. They arrived in the United
States when he was 5.
   ``My father was very perceptive. ... (He) came home the day
Hitler came to power and said we would leave Germany,'' Boschwitz
said.
   Boschwitz has no family left there and acknowledges having mixed
feelings about returning.
   ``For the first time, when he was sitting watching the
television pictures from Berlin and East Germany ... he felt the
real urge to go back,'' said Boschwitz' press secretary, Tim
Droogsma.
   Boschwitz will be accompanied on the trip by 12 Polish-speaking
dairy farmers he hopes can give some ``hands-on'' help to their
Polish counterparts. Cattle are still milked by hand in parts of
Poland.
   ``It's certainly going to take more than one visit, but first
you've got a sense of where they are,'' he said.
</TEXT>
