<FIRST>r a PM-Serviceman-Bombs     12-01 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Serviceman-Bombs,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bombs, Bandoleer, Survival Gear Found in Serviceman's Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military policeman found with 11 homemade
bombs in his car trunk was facing court-martial and had concocted
an escape plot in which he planned to lob the bombs at ``anyone in
his way,'' investigators said today.
   Senior Airman James Wilcox, 22, of Griffiss Air Force Base, was
arrested at the Park Inn motel in Rome Thursday night, police
officer Mike Dunn said.
   Wilcox was arrested after police were tipped that the airman had
homemade bombs in his car trunk, investigator James Masucci said.
   The bombs were made from carbon dioxide cartridges and were
``very dangerous,'' Masucci said. He would not be more specific.
   Wilcox was scheduled to be court-martialed Saturday on larceny
and house-breaking charges, said Griffiss spokesman Carl Sahre. The
airman told police he had planned to escape if he was found guilty,
Masucci said.
   The bombs were strapped to a bandoleer that Wilcox apparently
planned to wear so he could throw the explosives ``at patrol cars,
military police, civilians or anyone in his way,'' Masucci said.
   ``He had it right down to a science,'' the investigator said.
The bombs were stored in Wilcox's car along with a police scanner
and survival gear that would allow him to live in the woods and
evade searchers, Masucci said.
   ``I can't imagine why he would go through all this,'' Sahre
said. ``I can't see why he wouldn't just go AWOL if he was that
worried abut the court-martial.''
   Wilcox was put on limited duty as a base security officer after
his arrest on the theft charges in May, Sahre said. He was not
confined to quarters and was allowed to leave the base, he said.
   ``He could have taken off any time,'' Sahre said.
   The court-martial would go ahead as planned if Griffiss
officials can arrange to have Wilcox brought back to the base from
the Oneida County Jail, where he was being held, Sahre said.
   If convicted in the court martial, Wilcox could be confined at
Griffiss or sent to the military prison in Leavenworth, Kan., he
said.
   His arraignment on charges of criminal possession of dangerous
weapons was postponed from this morning until Monday.
</TEXT>
