<FIRST>u w PM-WorldAIDSDay 2ndLd-Writethru a0609 12-01 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-World AIDS Day, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0609,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Demonstrators Arrested in Front of the White House</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with arrests, CORRECTS name to Vaid sted Viad;
picks up at pvs 6th graf, Paul Boneberg</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 70 demonstrators were arrested today
after they sat down on Pennsylvania Avenue in front of the White
House to protest what they called the government's lack of
leadership in the AIDS epidemic.
   Those taking part in the civil disobedience were among some 200
people who attended a rally marking World AIDS Day.
   ``We're here because we're angry at our country and our
administration's response to this epidemic,'' said Urvashi Vaid of
the National Gay and Lesbian Task Force.
   The demonstration came a day after President Bush declared that
education is the nation's best weapon against AIDS.
   ``Our hearts go out to those afflicted, as our heads work toward
finding solutions,'' Bush said in a statement Thursday before
leaving for the Malta summit. ``In the meantime, we must continue
to educate those around us regarding the prevention of this
terrible disease.''
   ``Where are you, George?'' asked Ms. Vaid, leading the crowd in
Lafayette Park in a chant of ``Where is George? Where is George?''
   Paul Boneberg, executive director of Mobilization Against AIDS,
a San Francisco group, said, ``We do not have the resources in our
groups to meet this challenge. We see people who need treatment but
who are denied treatment....We see discrimination still across the
country, and there's no government response. It's shameful.''
   The groups said they would issue a ``report card'' giving Bush
failing grades for his response.
   Bush has failed to provide a national AIDS strategy, has not
pushed for adequate funding for prevention, care, research and
treatment and has not responded to the growing burden AIDS is
placing on the nation's health care system, said Rene Durazzo,
spokesman for more than a dozen groups, including the National
Association of People With AIDS and the AIDS Action Council.
   Health and Human Services Secretary Louis Sullivan said World
AIDS Day will provide an opportunity to reinforce preventive
measures and show compassion for those infected.
   More than 112,000 AIDS cases have been reported in the United
States, and more than 66,000 have died, Sullivan said.
   ``This is only the tip of the iceberg'' because the Public
Health Services estimates that about 1 million Americans may have
already been infected with the human immunodeficiency virus, or
HIV, that causes AIDS, Sullivan said.
   Though there is no cure, new treatments that can prolong the
lives of those infected make it more important those at risk get
tested, Sullivan said.
   ``AIDS and HIV will be with us for years to come,'' Sullivan
said. ``But each one of us can combat its further spread by making
wise choices about personal behavior _ choices based on the fact
that HIV is transmitted by having sex or sharing needles with an
infected partner.
   ``And, secure in the knowledge that HIV is not spread by casual,
non-sexual contact, each one of us can help lessen the impact of
AIDS by giving practical and compassionate help to those who have
been infected by HIV or who live with AIDS itself.''
   Bush, in his statement, acknowledged that though the AIDS
problem ``is great, and taxing our health care system now, far
greater difficulties await us in terms of human suffering and
provision of health care.''
   ``We have committed resources at an unprecedented rate to
HIV-related research of all kinds,'' he said, promising ``we will
continue the most vigorous research efforts.''
   ``At the same time, we must also educate and prevent. The
disease is spread through known ways, and it is clear that
education on the facts is our best means of combating AIDS at this
time,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
