<SECOND>AM-BRF--China-Executions,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>5 Executed in China For Disrupting Power Supply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five men were executed in northeastern China on
Friday for stealing equipment that resulted in power outages and
crop damage, an official report said.
   Zhou Mingyu and Liu Gang of Sulan county in Jilin province
destroyed seven transformers and stole 3,500 yards of wire in 1988,
the Xinhua News Agency said.
   That caused damage worth $5,400, cut power to 400 households in
six villages and interfered with the irrigation of 296 acres of
rice paddies, the report said.
   Three others _ an unidentified man and his two sons _ stole 19
transformers and 6,400 yards of cable and wire worth $11,000 in
1988, leaving 340 households without power and interrupting
irrigation of 500 acres of rice paddies, Xinhua said.
   The five were executed with the approval of the Jilin City
Municipal Court and Jilin province's higher court, according to the
report.
