<FIRST>u i PM-Nicaragua     12-01 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinista Refuse Visas For U.S. Election Observers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nicaraguan Foreign Ministry has
refused visas to a 20-member delegation appointed by President Bush
to observe next year's general election, saying such a panel would
not be impartial.
   ``From the point of view of his credibility before us, the very
fact that Mr. Bush has been the one to appoint this commission is
enough for it to be totally discredited,'' said a ministry
communique issued late Thursday.
   The communique said the vote Wednesday in the U.S. Congress to
continue non-lethal aid to the anti-Sandinista rebels, known as
Contras, ``will allow the Contras to keep infiltrating their bands
into Nicaragua to assassinate our people and create confusion in
the electoral process.''
   The general election is scheduled for Feb. 25.
   The Foreign Ministry also complained about $9 million approved
by Congress in October to aid the campaign of presidential
candidate Violeta Barrios de Chamorro of the United National
Opposition.
   UNO, as the 14-party bloc is known in English, is the strongest
challenger to the ruling Sandinista National Liberation Front.
   ``There exists a clear incompatilibity between pretending to buy
the election of a candidate while at the same time pretending to be
accepted as impartial observers in our elections,'' the communique
said.
   Scores of international observers have been invited to supervise
the elections, including teams from the United Nations, the
Organization of American States and the European Parliament.
   The communique said that the organizations and individuals
invited by the government of Nicaragua are experienced, honest and
impartial.
   ``The same, unfortunately, cannot be said of President Bush,
nor, therefore, of any commission appointed by him to observe the
elections in Nicaragua,'' the communique said.
   It said there are many ``genuine democrats'' in Congress and
``we trust in their capacity to understand that these declarations
are not in any way directed at them as individuals.''
</TEXT>
