<FIRST>u a PM-MassTaxes 1stLd-Writethru a0552 12-01 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mass Taxes, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0552,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Debate Opens on Scaling Back Tax Package</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with debate beginning. Picks up
4th graf, `The original...' </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state House began debate today after a one-day
delay on a tax package intended to raise more than a billion
dollars to fend off deficits resulting from the fizzling of the
``Massachusetts Miracle.''
   Speaker George Keverian lobbied all day Thursday without getting
enough votes to pass the package of sales, capital gains and
gasoline tax increases.
   The first amendment offered today was a proposal to strip a
capital gains tax increase worth $100 million a year from the bill,
which originally totaled $1.2 billion.
   ``This debate is the unfortunate, but inevitable conclusion of
not weeks, not months, but years of actions and inactions that
brought the Commonwealth of Massachusetts and this House to this
point,'' Republican leader Steven Pierce said in urging defeat of
the package. Pierce supported the amendment.
   The original House Ways and Means Committee package would have
raised the sales tax from 5 percent to 7 percent, increased the gas
tax by 10 cents over the next two years and hiked the capital gains
tax from 5 percent to 7.5 percent.
   Keverian said Democratic legislative leaders were considering
increasing the sales tax to 6 percent. He said the compromise would
cost $190 million in new revenue this fiscal year and about $400
million next year.
   Most increases would take effect Jan. 1, 1990, but the capital
gains tax hike would be retroactive to last January.
   Keverian said the loss would be made up with additional cuts and
possibly some additional revenue in the tax package. He would not
predict the outcome of a vote on an amendment he expects some House
members to offer to remove the capital-gains tax hike from the bill.
   The tax proposal was attached to a $45 million ``survival
package'' that would restore funds to social service and education
programs.
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis indicated he had some reservations about
the package, but urged lawmakers to approve it.
   Dukakis captured the 1988 Democratic presidential nomination in
part by touting his state's economic ``miracle.'' After the
election, Massachusetts' fiscal fortunes plummeted, partly because
of the end of a boom caused by the nation's military buildup.
   He said Thursday he realized taxes were unpopular, but urged
elected officials to take a tough stand and not make only the
popular votes.
   ``If there's anything we've got to have now it's fiscal
stability,'' Dukakis said. ``And that's what this package is going
to bring.''
   Keverian had told several committee chairmen they should resign
if they could not support it. Tax foes, including the House's
Republican minority, decried what they said were strong-arm tactics.
   Several lawmakers said the changes in the tax package were
needed to win support from a majority of the 160-member House.
   ``I think it is clear as the package stands, we are short of the
81 votes needed to pass it,'' said Rep. Marjorie Clapprood, a
supporter of the package.
   News of the package sent taxpayers to their telephones. One of
two switchboard operators at the Statehouse said she was handling
more than 100 calls every 15 minutes.
   Clapprood suggested shutting off the Statehouse switchboard and
locking lawmakers in the House chamber to get the tax bill passed.
</TEXT>
