<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1338EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MobilSpill     12-01 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mobil Spill,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mobil Pleads No Contest In Pipeline Spill Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mobil Oil Corp. pleaded no contest to
misdemeanor charges stemming from two pipeline ruptures that poured
more than 130,000 gallons of crude oil into the Los Angeles River
and the city's sewers.
   The pleas were entered Thursday in Los Angeles Municipal Court
on two violations of a state Fish and Game code section prohibiting
the release of petroleum or petroleum residue into state waters.
   Mobil attorney Ernest J. Getto said the pleas ``just mean we're
not going to contest the charges.''
   ``It's not at all tantamount to a guilty plea,'' he said.
   The maximum fine for each violation is $1,000. However, City
Attorney James Hahn said he would ask at Mobil's Jan. 4 sentencing
hearing that the company be ordered to pay $100,000 in cleanup
costs.
   ``We asked for the sentencing hearing to be delayed ... in order
to give the various agencies involved in the cleanup of spills the
time to prepare presentations for restitution from Mobil,'' Hahn
said in a prepared statement.
   Agencies involved in the cleanup were the U.S. Coast Guard,
state Department of Fish and Game, Los Angeles Police Department
and Los Angeles Fire Department.
   The first pipeline break occurred Sept. 10, 1988, in the
suburban Encino area and sent 90,000 gallons of crude oil onto city
streets. The oil eventually flowed into the sewers and the Los
Angeles River.
   The second occurred 17 days later as the pipeline was being
repaired.
   The line carries 2.6 million gallons of oil a day from Kern
County oil fields to Mobil's Torrance refinery.
   Temperature changes in the oil caused the pipeline to corrode
and rupture the first time, said Deputy City Attorney Vincent B.
Sato. He said there was no indication of negligence.
   Getto said the company has since revised its monitoring
procedures and has begun replacing older sections of the pipeline.
</TEXT>
