<DOCNO> AP891201-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1357EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0589 12-01 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0589,0765</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tom Stoppard's `Artist Descending a Staircase' Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 4 grafs with what other critics said. No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imagine a story that begins at the end and ends
at the beginning.
   That is the tricky dramatic framework Tom Stoppard has devised
for ``Artist Descending a Staircase,'' an intriguing 85-minute
entertainment that arrived Thursday at Broadway's Helen Hayes
Theater.
   The play is small in scale but superbly crafted, down to the
most minute production detail, particularly Tony Straiges'
intricate, Rube Goldberg-like settings. Although it doesn't have
the scope or characterizations of such major Stoppard efforts as
``The Real Thing'' or ``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead,''
it's a richly rewarding piece of theater.
   The evening is divided into 11 scenes which go from the present
to the past and then back again to the present. Stoppard wrote
``Artist Descending a Staircase'' for the radio 17 years ago, but
it was staged last year at a pub in North London and later in the
West End before making the trek to Broadway.
   ``Artist Descending a Staircase'' is a play about perception.
How three men _ all of them artists _ look at life, love and art.
And their views are just as fractured as the nude in Marcel
Duchamp's famous painting.
   ``Artist Descending a Staircase'' is also a mystery. Who did in
one of the artists, found dead at the bottom of the stairs as the
play opens? The riddle is eventually solved but not before Stoppard
examines the lives of the three men.
   Donner (John McMartin) is a born-again romantic, a one-time
member of the avant-garde who once carved edible sugar sculptures _
``It will give cubism a new lease on life,'' says one of the other
artists _ but who now has returned to more traditional forms of
portrait painting. Beauchamp (Harold Gould) is a ``sound'' artist,
tape recording the noises of everyday life. Martello (Paxton
Whitehead) concentrates on completing a hideous statue of a
long-dead girlfriend, using fake pearls for teeth and pears for
breasts.
   In his journey backward in time, Stoppard also puts the aging
artists' younger selves on stage. They are all infatuated with
Sophie, a blind girl who died in 1922 after falling out of a
window. She was in love with one of them. But which one? Reality is
quite different from belief, Stoppard says.
   The playwright has great fun making fun of artistic pretensions.
``Skill without imagination is craftsmanship,'' sniffs Donner.
``Imagination without skill gives us modern art.''
   McMartin, Gould and Whitehead are an appealing trio of cranky
old artists, particularly Whitehead, who turns Martello's
moroseness into high comic art. Their younger counterparts are
played by Michael Winther, Michael Cumpsty and Jim Fyfe. Their
resemblance to the older men is remarkable. And Stephanie Roth is
appealing as the tragic Sophie, the muse for most of these artists'
careers.
   Tim Luscombe has directed the play with astonishing skill.
Despite the complicated time sequence, it is always clear where and
when the characters are. Straiges' best set is the aging artists'
studio, an almost surreal room filled with old paintings, bicycle
wheels and assorted junk from creating 50 years of art.
   Special mention should go to Tharon Musser's lighting, which
makes the scene changes all the more dazzling, and the music and
sound effects by Kevin Malpass, which are an important part of the
story.
   Stoppard has called the play a love story, but it is more than
that. ``Artist Descending a Staircase'' is a memory play in which
the playwright swirls together the peculiar _ and very different _
memories of three friends and fellow artists. It makes for a heady
mixture, often witty and just a little bit sad.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   What other critics said:
   Frank Rich, The New York York Times: I don't have to tell you
that Mr. Stoppard is clever. In this 85-minute work, that
cleverness is not harnessed to a major play but to an often
stimulating, sporadically funny and, at one uncharacteristic
juncture, genuinely moving investigation of the nature of
perception, memory and art.
   Howard Kissel, Daily News: ``Artist Descending a Staircase'' ...
is like a Faberge egg; it is very much an artifact fashioned for
aristocratic temperaments. Its glittering surfaces reflect one
another gracefully, precisely, giving off glints of brilliant
color, hinting at unsuspected depths.
   Clive Barnes, New York Post: ... a play of shining wit, gleaming
intelligence and glintingly metallic heart.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
