<HEAD>Army Aircraft Crashes into River with Five Aboard</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with rescue efforts, no survivors.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON PARK, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A twin-engine Army plane with four
crew members and a civilian on board crashed into the Patuxent
River today, and no survivors had been found several hours later,
authorities said.
   The CASA-212 aircraft was headed to Patuxent Naval Air Station
from Fort Belvoir in northern Virginia when it crashed about 9:20
a.m., Army spokesman John Ooley said.
   The plane was lying in 45 feet of water early this afternoon
about 50 feet offshore from the air station, Ooley said.
   ``There were rescue boats and helicopters on the scene and
they've not brought anything up yet,'' Ooley said. He would not
identify those aboard until their families had been notified.
   The airplane was assigned to Davison Army Air Field at Fort
Belvoir, said John Romer, Naval Air Station deputy public affairs
officer.
