<DOCNO> AP891201-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1507EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Summit-NATOAllies     12-01 0782</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-NATO Allies,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>America's Allies Watch Summit With Apprehension About Europe's Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's NATO allies are keeping a
wary watch on this weekend's summit at Malta, concerned it might
produce a secret superpower agreement on Europe despite President
Bush's promise of ``no surprises.''
   Allies in Western Europe are worried the superpowers could cut a
deal that would include a hefty reduction of U.S. troops from
Europe, say diplomats and analysts.
   ``There's always apprehension among some allies when the big
kids get together,'' said Jane Sharp, senior researcher at the
Stockholm International Peace Research Institute in Sweden.
   Added one senior NATO official, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity: ``We're in such a critical historical period that
apprehension is running high regardless of what happens. (People)
just don't know what's coming.''
   U.S. allies would be quite content, in fact, to see Bush and
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's shipboard summit be a quiet
one, with no dramatic agreements.
   But, while U.S. officials have sought to minimize chances of a
superpower agreement, a top Kremlin official in Malta hinted Friday
that Gorbachev might use the weekend summit to try to nudge Bush
toward accords on the shape of Eastern Europe and on banning
nuclear weapons in the Mediterranean.
   ``The importance of achieving preliminary agreements on a host
of issues, including the Mediterranean and Europe, is of course
great and that is precisely the reason for our meeting,'' said
Valentin Falin, the head of the International Department of the
Soviet Communist Party.
   Bush has stressed that the summit will not focus on arms control
and that he would not spring any suprises on U.S. allies. The
president also has said he will not discuss Eastern Eurpopean
boundaries with Gorbachev.
   Gorbachev, however, is known for his unpredictability.
   Compounding the concern to U.S. allies is the memory of the 1986
summit in Reykjavik, when the Soviet leader caught then-President
Reagan off guard by unveilling sweeping arms control proposals. The
talks broke down over the Strategic Defense Initiative, also known
as Star Wars, but not until Reagan and Gorbachev had flirted with a
deal to do away with all nuclear weapons.
   The allies were furious such discussions took place without
consultations.
   ``Everything has been done to prevent that sort of horror
scenario,'' said a senior Dutch official at NATO, who demanded
anonymity.
   The weekend talks in the Mediterranean occur against a backdrop
of momentous political and economic change in the Soviet Union and
Eastern Europe. The crumbling of hardline regimes in East Germany,
Bulgaria and Czechoslovakia, combined with the earlier reforms in
Poland and Hungary, mean the military threat from the East has been
reduced dramatically. At the same time, the question of reshaping
borders and alliances has been raised.
   Wanting to make sure their voices weren't ignored, leaders of
the 12 nations of the European Community called an emergency summit
to discuss the changes in Eastern Europe.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher made a quick trip to
the United States to talk to Bush. Afterward, she said she did not
expect ``great or unusual pronouncements'' from Malta.
   Added French President Francois Mitterrand: ``It is normal and
desirable that they meet (but) I don't expect them to decide
(anything) in our place.''
   Bush will meet Monday in Brussels with other leaders of the
16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization to fill them in on his
talks.
   One NATO diplomat, demanding anonymity, said some Europeans were
concerned that a far-reaching ``kind of mindset or framework or
understanding'' would come out of the superpower summit and lead to
significant cuts in the number of American soldiers on the
continent.
   He said the allies were worried about trimming U.S. forces
beyond the levels under negotiation at conventional arms talks in
Vienna.
   The United States wants to wrap up an accord on conventional
armed forces in Europe by June. Defense Secretary Dick Cheney has
raised the possibility of a second set of negotiations to reduce
arms further.
   The Vienna bargaining between NATO and the Warsaw Pact is
designed to reduce the East's overwhelming superiority in tanks and
other conventional, or non-nuclear, arms in Europe. Both sides
would be brought down to equal levels under proposals on the table.
   As part of the talks, Bush suggested that the United States and
the Soviet Union pare their forces in Europe to 275,000 on each
side. That would require the Soviets to pull out 300,000 troops and
the United States 30,000.
   But Cheney left no doubt at a meeting this week of NATO defense
ministers that the United States, under heavy budget pressures,
would like to bring even more soldiers home.
</TEXT>
