<FIRST>r w AM-CPSC-ToySafety     12-01 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CPSC-Toy Safety,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>CPSC Says Recalls Rising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new chairwoman of the Consumer Product
Safety Commission said Friday that the government had more than
doubled recalls and other actions against dangerous toys and
children's products in this year.
   Delivering the CPSC's annual toy safety advisory, chairwoman
Jacqueline Jones-Smith said 254 toys and 119 children's products
had been the targets of recalls or corrective actions this year,
compared to 111 toys and 39 children's products in 1988.
   The commission made no recommendations against purchasing any
specific toys but advised people buying gifts for children to be
``mindful of the developmental level of the child'' in making their
selections.
   The agency offered theese tips for selecting and using toys:
   _Before buying a riding toy, be sure there is a safe place for
the child to ride it.
   _Keep games with small parts _ including marbles and balls _
away from young children, especially youngsters who tend to put
things in their mouths.
   _Don't allow unsupervised children to play with uninflated or
broken balloons, which could slip down a child's throat and choke
him.
   _Remove crib gyms and attached mobiles from a baby's crib as
soon as the youngster is five months old or can push up on his or
her hands and knees.
   Jones-Smith also said that more than a million ``unsafe toys
never made it to retail shelves'' because they had been seized in a
joint CPSC-Customs Service program.
   She noted the commission's nearly year-long lack of a quorum,
for which critics have chided the Bush Administration, and told
reporters:
   ``We are here today at full strength, energized and ready to
move. Reports of the commission's death were not premature _ they
were wrong.''
   Last week, the Consumer Affairs Committee of the Americans for
Democratic Action declared the CPSC ``officially dead'' because of
the ten-month lack of a quorum, which ended when Jones-Smith was
sworn in.
   Ending her first week on the job, Jones-Smith said the CPSC ``is
indeed alive and well and moving forward to enforce product safety
laws.''
   She acknowledged, however, that she had not developed priority
issues or programs for the commission to pursue.
   Commissioner Carol Dawson said the CPSC ``will act quickly to
dispose of pending business before it.''
   That includes a staff evaluation and recommendations on a
petition to ban crib gyms and developing methods to test the safety
of disposable cigarette lighters around children.
   The agency announced three toy recalls Friday.
   Two bicycles _ the Mountain Jr. 16-inch sidewalk model 1615,
imported from Taiwan by California-based Ming Ta Supply U.S.A., and
the BMX sidewalk models 121 and 124, manufactured by Texas-based
Sante Fe Trading, Inc., were recalled. Several safety features
missing from both bikes make them hazardous to young children, the
commission said.
   Also recalled were more than 8,000 eight-shot and 12-shot ring
caps manufactured by texas-based Daisy Manufacturing Co. and
distributed through Wal-Mart stores nationwide since October. The
agency said the caps may ignite prematurely from friction or if
dropped.
</TEXT>
