<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINCHESTER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Queen Elizabeth II, who prides
herself on being punctual, apologized to guests kept waiting for 25
minutes in the cold for the opening of an army regimental museum.
   But she had a good excuse.
   ``I came through fire, frost and fog to get here,'' she said.
   The queen, who is colonel in chief of the Royal Green Jackets,
was in Winchester, Hampshire, to open the regiment's newly extended
and refurbished museum.
   The royal car had to be diverted in west London because of a
fire and was then further delayed by fog on the M3 motorway.
   In her speech outside the museum, the queen recalled this was
the second time she had been invited to speak to the regiment
outdoors on a wintry morning, and said: ``It's a tribute to the
hardiness of the Green Jackets.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trumpeter Wynton Marsalis, whose new album, ``A
Crescent City Christmas Card,'' highlights his New Orleans'
beginnings, scoffs at artists who scout the world in search of
musical roots or influences.
   ``That's fake,'' Marsalis said in the Dec. 1-3 issue of USA
Weekend. ``Most of that stuff is based on racial exploitation. In
order to deal with the music of another culture, you have to be
that. You know, I could listen to some Chinese music and give you a
facsimile of it, but it's not going to have the soul of that
music.''
   In the same issue, Branford Marsalis blamed the media for
reports of a rift between him and his brother when he quit Wynton
Marsalis' band to play with Sting in 1985.
   ``The press tries to trip you up. Wynton just doesn't answer and
I answer with a joke, so he's arrogant and I'm the fun-loving
one,'' Branford Marsalis said. For the record, he added, ``I'm more
arrogant and opinionated than him.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zsa Zsa Gabor is finding that crime doesn't
pay.
   The actress got more publicity from her notorious cop-slapping
trial in Beverly Hills than from any entertainment projects in
years, but book, movie and TV offers don't appear to be flooding in.
   Miss Gabor, a onetime Hungarian beauty queen, was sentenced to
serve three days in jail and perform court-ordered community
service after she was found guilty of slapping a police officer
trying to issue her a traffic citation.
   A videotape documenting her trial, which was punctuated by
frequent outbursts from the actress, hasn't been a hot seller, said
Tower Records video sales clerk Mark Elliott. ``From what I can
see, nobody's buying it.''
   ``Who wants to run Zsa Zsa pictures now?'' said celebrity
photographer Peter Borsari. ``I even couldn't sell one of Milton
Berle putting his hand over her mouth that was taken at Sidney
Sheldon's party at Jimmy's.''
   A publicist for Miss Gabor, Phil Paladino, said sales of the
face cream and cubic zirconia gift set bearing her name have
slumped.
   Miss Gabor is to appear in two movies, said agent Cal Ross, but
the parts were signed before the trial. A deal for an
autobiography, negotiated before her arrest, is in limbo because of
editorial differences, Ross said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Luciano Pavarotti's need for sleep
silenced a noisy construction project in Portland this week.
   The tenor arrived Tuesday in Portland, two days before he was to
sing for a benefit concert for the Portland Opera. At a news
conference shortly after his arrival, Pavarotti said that sleep was
important to protect his voice.
   The Oregonian newspaper reported that the manager for the
Heathman Hotel, where Pavarotti was staying, was so concerned about
his sleep that she got a pile-driver to stop operating near the
building.
   The paper said hotel manager Mary Arnstad called the owner of
the Hoffman Construction Co., which is building a 23-story building
across from the hotel, and asked that crews quit using the
pile-driver from 7:30 a.m. to 10:30 a.m. on Wednesday and Thursday,
and the owner agreed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kathleen Turner and Michael Douglas were so into
their roles as a quarreling couple in ``War of the Roses'' that
they had to make up daily.
   ``We made a point of saying to each other at the end of the day,
`It's OK, I still like you,'' Turner said in an interview in the
Dec. 1-3 issue of USA Weekend.
   Douglas and Turner, first paired in ``Romancing the Stone,''
play an unsympathetic divorcing couple in ``Roses.''
   While the two say they are friends, things were not so cozy when
Turner first refused to do ``Jewel of the Nile,'' the sequel to
``Stone.''
   The two stars met to work out differences.
   ``We got drunk and said we hated each other, that we would never
agree on this but that it was fine,'' said Turner, who made the
sequel. ``And obviously we resolved it because here we are.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bet on a diet turned into an all-star
tribute for Los Angeles Dodgers Manager Tommy Lasorda to benefit an
order of Catholic nuns.
   ``It's been beneficial to me. I went from a 40 waist to a
35-inch waist. I went from a 17-inch neck to a 15{. I feel so good
it scares me,'' Lasorda said.
   His ``Tommy Lasorda Grand Slam Variety Show'' at the Grand Ole
Opry House Thursday raised $50,000 to build a new center for the
Sisters of Mercy. The fund-raiser grew from a bet made during
spring training between Lasorda, Dodger pitcher Orel Hershiser and
outfielder Kirk Gibson.
   They offered to donate $10,000 each to his favorite charity if
Lasorda could lose 30 pounds by the All-Star break in July. The
Dodger manager ended up losing 40 pounds and decided to help the
Sisters of Mercy in Nashville at the suggestion of a friend.
   Hershiser, Gibson, singers Vic Damone, Roy Acuff, Kathy Mattea
and Ricky Van Shelton wre among the celebrities at the event.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kitty Dukakis put her own troubles behind her when
she was honored as New England Woman of the Year in recognition of
the help she has given homeless people and refugees.
   The wife of Gov. Michael S. Dukakis appeared Thursday night at
her second public engagement in as many days since her
hospitalization last month after drinking rubbing alcohol.
   Mrs. Dukakis, 52, accompanied by her husband, said her work and
the experiences of those she's helped ``illustrate how lives can be
changed when we work together. Facing life's challenges can be
difficult and extremely stressful.''
   In 1983, Dukakis named his wife to head his committee on
homelessness. She was instrumental in pushing for a statewide
network of community-based family shelters. In January 1983, there
was only one family shelter statewide; today there are more than
100.
</TEXT>
