<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1445EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i MalteseStrainToSeePresidentTheyHopeWillMakeittleTalkofRecession
    12-01 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>Maltese Strain To See President They Hope Will Make History In</SECOND>
<TEXT>
   Malta
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSAXLOKK BAY, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maltese, old and young, skipped
work and cut school Friday to catch a glimpse of the American
president they hoped would focus the world's attention on their
tiny island nation,
   Maltese security kept the crowds away from the airport hanger
area when Bush arrived during a cold rain. But several thousand
lined the streets near the Auberge Castile, the 16th Century palace
where Bush talked with Prime Minister Edward Fenech Adami. Some
cheered, some shouted his name and a few stood singing the Maltese
national anthem as Bush emerged from the palace and waved to the
crowd.
   Hundreds of other people gathered along the shoreline or on
roads along the cliffs that overlook the bay where Bush will meet
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev aboard Soviet and American
warships over the weekend.
   ``I can't believe he is coming to here, to Malta. He is such a
big man, an important man. We are so lucky,'' said Marika Galea, a
22-year-old Maltese housewife.
   ``This is very important because we are a small island and now
all over the world, because of television and newspapers, everyone
in the world will know what Malta is,'' she said.
   Bush was greeted at the airport by Maltese President Vincent
Tabone, Prime Minister Fenech Adami and a military band and honor
guard that stood in the rain for more than an hour in their full
dress uniform while waiting for the American leader.
   After the brief ceremony, Bush left by helicopter for the
meeting at the Auberge Castile and then to the aircraft carrier USS
Forrestal in the Mediterranean.
   Aboard the carrier Bush dined with the enlisted men in their
mess and watched flight operations from an outdoor platform high
above the flight deck. Bush had been waving to the crew and
standing at mock attention when a jet crossed low in front of the
carrier at supersonic speed.
   The enormous sonic boom startled the president. He ducked, his
knees buckled and then he turned and smiled at the TV cameras with
a sheepish grin.
   From the carrier, Bush flew directly to Marsaxlokk Bay and the
USS Belknap, the guided missile cruiser where Bush will host the
Kremlin leader for talks and a state dinner Saturday night.
   Two Maltese patrol boats kept small boats away from the Belknap
and the Soviet missile cruiser Slava, which is anchored a few
hundred yards in front of the American ship. Navy frogmen dove
beneath the Belknap or motored around a few hundred yards away in
small rubber boats.
   Maltese soldiers armed with automatic rifles patrolled the
shoreline and cliffs above the bay. Two sharpshooters stood atop a
16th Century watchtower that looks out over the bay from a cliff
that marks the closest point of land to the warships.
   ``This is something we may never see again,'' said Mansel
Cappell of Liverpool, England, as the president's helicopter landed
on the Belknap. He said he and his wife spent two hours taking two
city buses to reach a fishing village by the bay.
   ``We came to see this great day and to take a picture,'' he
said. ``Then, when we go home we can say we were here in Malta.''
   ``I'll keep this in my mind, I'll never forget,'' said Mrs.
Galea as she strained through binoculars to see the president
aboard the warship.
   Others at Marsaxlokk took a more commercial view of the summit.
One man hawked summit T-shirts from the back of a van in front of
the watch tower and others sold sandwiches, cold drinks and donuts.
   One enterprising Maltese, John Itso, did a brisk business
selling white china plates emblazoned with a picture of either the
Slava or the Belknap. Before the president arrived, he sold 400 of
the 500 plates he brought to Marsaxlokk on Friday.
   ``We worked all night to get these out,'' said Itso, ``but we've
had quite a good sale.''
</TEXT>
