<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     12-01 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hrawi Tries to Avoid Showdown Between Aoun and Syrians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elias Hrawi, Lebanon's new president, has
asked the United States, Soviet Union and France to convince Gen.
Michel Aoun to avoid another battle with Syrian forces, a source
close to Hrawi said Friday.
   He said Hrawi said he was ``trying to avoid a military showdown,
but at the same time, he is determined to regain control of all
government institutions in the Christian area.''
   Hrawi sent letters to President Bush, Soviet President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev and French President Francois Mitterrand, asking that
they urge Aoun to leave the presidential palace, the government
source said.
   ``The president was elected to supervise implementation of a
peace plan, not to declare war,'' said the source, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. ``Aoun, who opposes the peace plan, wants
war.''
   He was referring to a peace accord worked out by Lebanese
lawmakers in Taif, Saudi Arabia, in October. Aoun rejected it
because it did not include a specific timetable for withdrawal of
the 40,000 Syrian soldiers stationed in Lebanon.
   An-Nahar, an independent newspaper, said France had asked the
United States and Soviet Union to ``exert relentless efforts to
prevent a new military collision in Lebanon.'' France governed
Lebanon under mandate for more than 20 years until independence in
1943.
   Young Christians maintained a human shield Friday around the
presidential palace, where Aoun has his living quarters and command
post in a bunker.
   Aoun led a Christian government in competition with a Moslem
cabinet while Lebanon was without a president for 14 months. He
refused to leave the palace in Baabda, a Christian surburb east of
Beirut, after Hrawi was elected by Parliament and dismissed him as
army commander.
   Other Christians in cars demonstrated in the Ashrafiyeh district
of east Beirut to support Samir Geagea, who has pledged the 6,000
men of his Lebanese Forces militia to help Aoubn defend the
310-square-mile Christian enclave against a Syrian attack.
   About 20,000 Christian troopers of the Lebanese army followed
the general in a six-month artillery war with the Syrians that
killed nearly 1,000 people, nearly all of them civilians.
   The youths at the palace sang Lebanon's national anthem and
waved placards with such slogans as ``Syrians go home'' and ``The
general is our only leader.''
   Geagea's supporters carried placards reading ``The leader of
free Lebanon.''
   The militia leader, whose group is the largest Christian
fighting force outside the army, said he was against armed conflict
and told supporters at an east Beirut school: ``With dialogue we
can solve any problem.''
   In Jerusalem, military and political leaders said Friday a
Syrian buildup in Lebanon over the past several days did not
threaten Israel and a Syrian attack on Christian forces was not
likely to bring an Israeli response.
   Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron, the chief of staff, said: ``Israel will
not act as long as its essential interests are not threatened. At
this stage, they are not.''
   Hrawi, a Christian the Syrians support, was elected a week ago
and formed a national reconciliation government led by Prime
Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, to implement the peace plan.
He dismissed Aoun as armed forces commander Tuesday and replaced
him with Adm. Emile Lahoud.
   Aoun contends that Hrawi's election was unconstitutional and has
refused to accept his decisions.
   Syria has sent thousands more soldiers into Lebanon, along with
tanks and artillery, apparently getting ready for a showdown with
Aoun. The Syrians have been in Lebanon since 1976, the year after
Lebanon's sectarian civil war began, under a peacekeeping mandate
from the Arab League.
</TEXT>
