<FIRST>r w AM-AIDS-WhiteHouse     12-01 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-White House,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Activists Arrested in Pennsylvania Avenue Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Art-AIDS, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of AIDS activists shouting ``Where is
George?'' were arrested Friday after they sat in the street in
front of the White House to protest what they say is President
Bush's lack of leadership.
   Many of the 78 arrested are directors and top officials of AIDS
groups from across the country who say their organizations need
more money for prevention efforts and to continue providing health
and social services to a growing number of people with AIDS.
   ``Rhetoric is not what we need. Action is what we need,'' said
Tim Sweeney of the Gay Men's Health Crisis in New York told about
200 protesters who gathered in Lafayette Park across from the White
House at a rally marking World AIDS Day.
   ``We do not have the resources in our groups to meet this
challenge,'' said Paul Boneberg, executive director of Mobilization
Against AIDS, a San Francisco group. ``We see people who need
treatment but who are denied treatment ... We see discrimination
still across the country, and there's no government response. It's
shameful.''
   Speakers at the rally mocked Bush's statement, issued Thursday
for World AIDS Day, in which he expressed compassion for people
with AIDS and said the government is committed to continuing
virorous research efforts.
   Protesters shouted, ``Lies, lies, lies.''
   Jean McGuire, executive director of the AIDS Action Council,
graded Bush's efforts to fight the AIDS epidemic, giving him an
``F.'' She said he failed to increase access to new treatments that
can prolong the lives of people with AIDS and did not provide
enough money for prevention and education as well as research and
health care for people with the disease.
   ``All you can give him is an `F' for a national AIDS strategy,''
she said. ``Moving into this second decade, there is no excuse not
to have one.''
   More than 112,000 AIDS cases have been reported in the United
States since the first cases were identified in 1981, and more than
66,000 have died. No one is known to have recovered from the
disease, which is spread primarily through sex and needles shared
with infected partners.
   The Public Health Service has estimated that more than 1 million
Americans may have already been infected with the human
immunodeficiency virus, or HIV.
   AIDS activists say the growing number of people with AIDS is
already straining health care services and that this burden is
guaranteed to get worse in the 1990s as more of those infected with
HIV become sick with AIDS.
   ``If your compassion doesn't move you, let your calculator move
you,'' Sweeney said.
   After the rally, demonstrators walked to Pennsylvania Avenue,
which had been blocked off by police, where some protesters used
chalk to draw the outlines of bodies in the street. They then sat
down, joined in chanting with the rest of the crowd lining the
street and waited to be arrested.
   Police who made the arrests wore rubber gloves, a standard
precaution District of Columbia police have taken in any mass
arrest since a 1987 AIDS demonstration, as they handcuffed the
protesters, some of whom had to be dragged to waiting buses.
   Police said 78 people were charged with blocking a public
roadway, the maximum penalty for which is 90 days in jail and a
$250 fine.
</TEXT>
