<FIRST>r i AM-Gorbachev-Raisa     12-01 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev-Raisa,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet First Lady Disappoints Fashion Crowd</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PIERO VALSECCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raisa Gorbachev on Friday switched from a
red dress that raised eyebrows at the Vatican to a green one as she
flew to Milan, one of Europe's fashion capitals.
   The Soviet first lady, normally known for her fashionable
clothes, surprised Italians with her austere look and few changes
of clothes during a three-day state visit to Italy.
   Contrary to the hopes of many Milanese designers, Mrs. Gorbachev
did not go shopping in Via della Spiga, Milan's fashion boulevard.
Shopping in the luxury, downtown street of this northern city was
not part of her official program but had been considered likely.
   Instead, the enthusiasm of swelling crowds, which slowed down an
crowded schedule for Mikhail S. Gorbachev and his wife in Italy's
economic capital, forced her to cut short her private tour.
   Mrs. Gorbachev joined her husband for his historic meeting with
Pope John Paul II at the Vatican wearing a red dress and going
against normal protocol of dressing in black. She changed,
apparently on the flight to Milan, into a business-like green
outfit.
   Hundreds of Milanese, including city art superintendent Rosalba
Tardito, waited in vain for Mrs. Gorbachev in chilly weather
outside Santa Maria delle Grazie church, in whose refectory
Leonardo da Vinci painted ``The Last Supper.''
   The visit to the fresco was canceled at the last minute because
Mrs. Gorbachev had been running behind the schedule after paying
homage to the Milanese home of the late Soviet artist Nicola Benois.
   About 300 people shouted ``Raisa! Raisa!'' when Mrs. Gorbachev
laid a bouquet of flowers below a marble plaque dedicated to
Benois, who had worked for several years with Milan's La Scala
opera house after leaving his native country.
</TEXT>
