<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Ivory     12-01 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Ivory,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>De Klerk Meets With Ivory Coast President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT WELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAMOUSSOUKRO, Ivory Coast (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South African President F.W. de
Klerk was greeted by hundreds of children singing ``Long live
dialogue!'' before he met Friday with President Felix
Houphouet-Boigny.
   Houphouet-Boigny met de Klerk as he stepped off the plane in the
95 degree heat in Yamoussoukro, the president's native village, for
the talks.
   South Africa and the Ivory Coast don't have formal diplomatic
relations, but they do have close trade ties. South African
Airways, barred from flying over most of the continent, is
permitted one flight a week to Abidjan, the capital of the Ivory
Coast.
   A front-page editorial in Friday's government-controlled daily
Fraternite Matin appeared to rule out closer diplomatic relations
for now.
   It said South Africa would not be able to normalize relations
with other African nations until it frees imprisoned black
nationalist Nelson Mandela, lifts the country's state of emergency,
and begins talks with legitimate representatives of the black
majority.
   The newspaper said Houphouet-Boigny would urge de Klerk to
``advance resolutely on the path of reforms already undertaken and
whose echo has already begun to shake the citadel of apartheid.''
   ``Everthing depends on de Klerk. ... Does he have the means to
follow through on this policy? Apparently yes,'' the newspaper said.
   Houphouet-Boigny has long advocated talks with South Africa to
dismantle that nation's legal system of racial separation known as
apartheid. But he also opposes sanctions to force South Africa into
giving equal rights to blacks.
   The newspaper said South Africa's strong economy and
technological base can help the continent. South Africa already has
supplied Ivory Coast with animals for a national park, a project
close to the heart of Houphouet-Boigny.
   The Ivory Coast's economy has been near collapse because of the
fall in prices for its main exports, cocoa and coffee, and needs
substantial aid.
   Thousands of people lined the wide avenues of Yamoussoukro to
welcome de Klerk on what was called the first official visit by a
South African head of state since the early 1970s. Buses brought
many to the town, 120 miles north of Abidjan.
   Houphouet-Boigny wants to make the village the nation's capital.
He already has built several large, ornate buildings, and workers
recently completed construction of a basilica that rivals St.
Peter's in the Vatican in size.
   De Klerk was scheduled to leave Saturday morning.
</TEXT>
