<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-US     12-01 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-US,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Took Over Homes of 3 U.S. Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas took over
the homes of two U.S. Embassy officials during their invasion of
San Salvador's affluent neighborhoods this week, diplomatic sources
said Friday.
   They also occupied the house of a former U.S. defense attache
who now works for the Salvadoran military, the sources said.
   The U.S. embassy believes that, in the case of one of the
diplomats and the former attache, the rebels stormed and occupied
the houses at random, as they did with more than two dozen other
homes in the wealthy districts invaded before dawn Wednesday.
   But they suspect the third house, described as that of a
``high-ranking official,'' was a specific target.
   They would not identify the resident of the sprawling home in
the San Benito neighborhood, a half-mile from the residence of U.S.
Ambassador William Walker. The house was a charred shell after
combat in and around it between leftist rebels and government
forces.
   Diplomatic sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said the
residents of the home retreated to a ``safe haven'' in the house
when they realized it was under attack. They said the residents
were never in rebel hands and that government forces forced the
guerrillas to retreat and then rescued the Americans.
   It was unclear if the retreating rebels set the house afire or
if it caught fire as a result of the combat.
   Journalists who inspected the burned house after the fire was
put out Wednesday found mail on the floor addressed to a person
with the surname Hultslander.
   Embassy spokespeople refused to confirm that a person of that
name lived in the house, or even worked at the embassy.
   Because the resident was described as a high-ranking embassy
official and because no journalist, even those in El Salvador for
years, knew that an embassy official lived there or knew of an
official named Hultslander, the suspicion was that the house was
that of a high-ranking officer of the CIA or another intelligence
branch.
   In Escalon, an affluent neighborhood next to San Benito, rebels
before dawn Wednesday took over the houses of midranking political
officer Vince Carver and George Maynes, a retired U.S. Army colonel
and former U.S. defense attache here.
   Both men left their homes shortly after 6 a.m. Thursday during a
truce declared by the rebels to permit evacuation.
   Carver identified himself as a U.S. diplomat when the rebels
broke in. He was allowed to take refuge with the maid in her room
at the rear of the house, where they stayed most of the next 26
hours. Street fighting outside was fierce at times.
   The burned hulk of a light tank destroyed by a rebel rocket sat
just down the street from Carver's house. The facade of the
diplomat's house, like most houses on the street, was scarred with
bullet holes, and the door appeared to have been blown open.
   Guerrillas had abandoned the house by the time Carver and his
maid left Thursday morning.
   Maynes' wife, Rosy, told The Associated Press on Thursday that
when she and her husband emerged from their home guerrillas
remained in the rear of the house and were treating some wounded
there.
   Diplomatic sources said the rebels apparently never knew that
Maynes, a New Mexico native who speaks fluent Spanish and who has
spent many years in Central America, was a retired U.S. Army
officer or former attache.
   Maynes teaches at the Salvadoran armed forces School of Military
Studies.
</TEXT>
