<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-AIDS     12-01 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-AIDS,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Princess Diana Mingles With AIDS Sufferers in New Hospital Ward</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Art-AIDS, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Princess Diana chatted and joked with AIDS victims
Friday as she opened a new ward at St. Mary's Hospital on World
AIDS Day.
   ``She was so visibly concerned, and she gave enormous confidence
to people who otherwise feel alienated and cast aside,'' said Dr.
Anthony Pinching, a clinical immunologist at the hospital.
   ``A handshake from her is worth 100,000 words from us,'' he said.
   The ward has 20 beds, 16 for people with AIDS or the virus that
leads to AIDS, and was designed after consultations with AIDS
patients.
   Diana sat on patients' beds, clasped their hands and listened to
their stories.
   She commented on the brightly colored shorts worn by one
patient, a 28-year-old barman with badly scarred and bandaged legs.
When he said they were his ``daywear,'' the princess replied, ``God
knows what you wear at night.''
   Full-page advertisements warning that thousands of people in
Britain don't know they are infected with the AIDS virus appeared
in newspapers Friday.
   ``We know of 11,218 people in the U.K. who have been infected
with the virus that leads to AIDS. It's the number we don't know
that is even more worrying,'' said the ad, placed by the
government's Health Education Authority.
   Experts have estimated that between 20,000 and 50,000 people in
Britain are infected with the virus.
</TEXT>
