<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1757EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Malaysia-American     12-01 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Malaysia-American,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Facing Drug Charges in Malaysia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney asked a court Friday
to allow U.S. Embassy officials to meet with his American client
who is accused of possessing 16.74 ounces of marijuana and faces
the death sentence if convicted.
   Kerrey Lane Wiley of Sacramento, Calif., is being held on the
tentative charge at Pudu Prison in Kuala Lumpur.
   Under Malaysian law, a person can be tentatively charged until a
firm charge has been drawn up, working out details such as what
section of the law allegedly was violated.
   Karpal also sought permission to meet privately with Wiley and
to allow a psychologist to examine him.
   Karpal made the same request at the magistrates court here where
Wiley appeared Thursday. The magistrate turned him down.
   Wiley, 37, teaches computer programming at a college in Hawaii.
He was passing through Malaysia and visiting a friend when he was
arrested Nov. 4.
   No date was set for the higher court to hear Karpal's appeal,
but Wiley's next court appearance was scheduled Dec. 28.
   Karpal said he hoped by then the attorney general would have
decided whether to charge Wiley with trafficking, which mandates
the death penalty, or another law that carries a lighter sentence.
   In Malaysia there is no need to prove trafficking. Mere
possession of 200 grams, or 7.05 ounces, of marijuana is deemed to
be trafficking.
   The stringent law was introduced in 1975. Since then, 244 people
have been sentenced to death. Of these 81 have been hanged,
including two Australians and a Briton. The others are awaiting
dates for hanging or appeals.
   Wiley was the first American to be charged under the law.
</TEXT>
