<FIRST>r w AM-Grain-Soviets     12-01 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain-Soviets,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Corn, Soybean Meal Sold to Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private exporting companies have sold the
Soviet Union an additional 800,000 metric tons of U.S. corn for
delivery in 1989-90 under a long-term supply agreement, the
Agriculture Department said Friday.
   The department said 100,000 tons of soybean meal also were sold
to the Soviet Union for 1989-90 delivery.
   Orders since Oct. 1, the beginning of the agreement's new year,
now total about 10.3 million tons of corn, 160,700 tons of
soybeans, 705,000 tons of soybean meal and 7,100 tons of barley.
   The sales, on the heels of orders announced Thursday for 1.4
million tons of corn and 150,000 tons of soybean meal, come as U.S.
and Soviet officials prepare to huddle next week in Moscow on grain
trade between the two countries.
   Department officials said the meetings will be held Tuesday and
Wednesday and will include discussions of ``a potential new
long-term grain agreement'' to succeed the current pact, which is
due to expire Dec. 31, 1990.
   U.S. grain sales to Moscow in 1988-89 were a record of more than
21.7 million tons, including more than 16.3 million tons of corn
and nearly 5.4 million tons of wheat.
   In addition, 1988-89 sales included 298,700 tons of soybeans,
1.35 million tons of soybean meal and 1.02 million tons of grain
sorghums.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 800,000 tons of
corn would be about 31.5 million bushels.
   The new sales were made by unidentified private exporting
companies, which are required to report large sales to the
department. No selling prices or other details were released.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.25 per bushel at the
farm, according to USDA's five-day average, meaning that the latest
sale could have a farm value of about $1.8 million.
   The soybean meal, at around $200 per ton at processing plants,
would have a value of about $20 million.
</TEXT>
