<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     12-01 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary to Cut Military By Up to One-Fourth</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Miklos Nemeth said Friday his
country would reduce its military strength by 20 percent to 25
percent by 1991, the state MTI news agency reported.
   Nemeth told Defense Ministry officials and army commanders that
Hungary would continue to coordinate its defense with its allies in
the Wasaw Pact alliance ``as long as the two military blocs
exist,'' MTI said.
   Nemeth's announcement came two days after the defense ministers
of the seven Warsaw Pact nations ended a regular meeting in
Budapest.
   Nemeth said Hungary's unilateral decision to reduce its army
strength by 20 percent to 25 percent was designed to promote
success at East-West negotiations under way in Vienna on
conventional arms reduction.
   Nemeth also said mandatory military service would be reduced
starting in 1991 from 18 months to 12 months, MTI reported.
   Last week, a chief military officer was quoted as saying the
Hungarian troop level was to be cut by 9 percent by the end of 1990.
   The Soviet Union began withdrawing some if its troops in Hungary
in April as part of a disarmament plan announced by Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev for the unilateral withdrawal of
500,000 troops by the end of 1990.
   That is to include 50,000 Soviet troops and 5,000 tanks from
Eastern Europe.
   Jozsef Biro, head of the tactical staff of the army general
staff, told the the Esti Hirlap daily newspaper: ``The stationing
of Soviet troops on Hungarian soil ... no longer has domestic
reasons.''
   ``Now their being stationed here has to do with maintaining the
strategic balance,'' he said.
   He said the Soviet Union has already withdrawn more than 10,000
troops of its estimated 62,000 troops, 470 tanks and 270 artillery
weapons.
</TEXT>
