<FIRST>r i AM-Peru-Memorial     12-01 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru-Memorial,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Memorial Erected to Wife of Jersey City, N.J., Mayor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CUZCO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city erected a memorial Friday to the
wife of a New Jersey mayor killed a year ago when a train carrying
her and her husband was derailed by saboteurs.
   Anna Cucci was killed and her husband, then-Mayor Anthony Cucci
of Jersey City, N.J., was injured when the rail car they were
riding in tumbled down a 250-foot ravine near Cuzco, 355 miles
southeast of Lima in the Andes Mountains.
   The monument christened Friday also commemorates the wife of
Cuzco's mayor, Doris Mayorga de Chacon, who also was killed. The
monument was erected in the Plaza of American Brotherhood in
downtown Cuzco.
   The rail car was derailed when it hit a 10-inch steel rod wedged
into the tracks. Authorities said the rod probably was placed by
leftist rebels or striking rail workers. No one has been charged in
the deaths.
   The Cuccis were visiting Cuzco to sign a sister city accord
between Jersey City and Cuzco. Six other people were injured when
the car derailed on its way to the ancient Incan citadel of Machu
Picchu, located 60 miles northwest of Cuzco.
   Mayor Carlos Chacon, who was injured in the derailment, presided
at a ceremony unveiling the two plaques, one in English and one in
Spanish. Chacon called the two women ``martyrs of American
brotherhood.''
</TEXT>
