<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1702EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-UN-PLO     12-01 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-PLO,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab Nations Postpone UN Vote on PLO Resolution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab nations on Friday postponed a General
Assembly vote on recognizing the PLO as the government of Palestine
just two hours before it was scheduled.
   One Western diplomat, speaking privately, said a rift has
developed between PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat and Farouk Khaddoumi,
the PLO foreign secretary who heads the Palestinian U.N. delegation.
   Khaddoumi has been trying to line up the votes for the
resolution, while Arafat believes the effort is counterproductive
and has ordered a halt, the source said.
   The State Department has said it will cut off all U.S. funds to
the United Nations if the resolution passes. The United States is
assessed $216 million annually, a quarter of the U.N budget.
   After the 22-nation Arab League held a private meeting, its
ambassador, Clovis Maksoud, announced the resolution would instead
be put to a vote Monday.
   ``This is final, categorical and unequivocal,'' said Maksoud.
   The delay is intended to allow non-aligned nations to receive
voting instructions, he said. Diplomats said it would also give the
Palestine Liberation Organization more time to lobby its allies for
support.
   However, Western diplomats said the delay actually helps the
United States, 12 European Community nations and Nordic countries
that are trying to derail the resolution.
   As a member of the 102-member Non-Aligned Movement, the PLO
theoretically has more than enough votes to prevail on a majority
vote in the 159-member General Assembly.
   Western diplomats, however, say any vote will be extremely close
and refuse to predict whether the resolution will pass.
   Maksoud acknowledged the United States has had some success
fighting the resolution.
   ``The United States has put us in a serious dilemma, with
threatening to cut the budget to stifle debate,'' he said.
   The Soviet Union opposes the resolution, and Egypt and Morocco
have not yet endorsed it.
   John Bolton, the State Department undersecretary for
International Organizations, said Friday, ``We continue to oppose
this resolution and believe it should be withdrawn.
   ``We are maintaining intensive efforts to insure that this is
not adopted,'' he said. He reiterated the threat to cut off all
U.N. funding.
   ``A number of other countries are also working in this
direction,'' Bolton said.
   The proposed resolution says the PLO ``has the powers and
responsibilities of the Provisional Government of the State of
Palestine.''
   It also says the PLO ``shall be construed, within the United
Nations, as the State of Palestine.''
   That designation would elevate the PLO from its current status
as a non-voting observer nation. Also holding such status are North
and South Korea, Switzerland, Monaco, San Marino and the Vatican.
   Last year, the PLO declared the state of Palestine in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip but did not define any
borders. Khaddoumi says more than 80 nations have formally
recognized Palestine.
</TEXT>
