<FIRST>r i AM-Gorbachev-Helsinki     12-01 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev-Helsinki,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Finland Says `Hesinki 2' Can Be Ready Next Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation of Finland will be able to
hold the 35-nation summit next year as proposed by Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the foreign minister said Friday.
   Provided that the nations in the Conference on Security and
Cooperation in Europe agree, ``Finland would have the technical
capability of hosting the summit next year,'' said Foreign Minister
Pertti Paasio.
   Paasio said a joint declaration issued during Gorbachev's state
visit to Finland in October called on Finland to stage a summit in
conjunction with the opening of the Helsinki follow-up meeting in
1992.
   On Thursday, Gorbachev proposed that such a summit be brought
forward to next year because of the swift developments in Eastern
Europe. He did not specify Helsinki as a venue.
   The last conference resulted in the 1975 Helsinki accords on
human rights and confidence-building measures between East and West.
   The countries that signed the 1975 Helsinki accords are the
Soviet Union, the United States, Canada and all the European
nations except Albania.
