<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Jarvefelt     12-01 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Jarvefelt,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opera Director Goran Jarvefelt Dead at Age 42</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Goran Jarvefelt, one of Sweden's
youngest and most promising opera directors, has died of cancer at
the age of 42.
   Jarvefelt, who was suffering from a brain tumor, died Thursday.
   He had established himself at leading world operas, including
the New York Metropolitan Opera, the Paris Opera and Komische Oper
in East Berlin. He worked with both classical and contemporary
themes.
   ``He avoided the easy solutions. He always sought new paths to
approach the core of the work,'' said Swedish opera star Sylvia
Lindenstrand.
   Jarvefelt was born in Bollnas, in central Sweden. He began as an
actor but changed careers after becoming fascinated by opera.
   He studied under successful directors abroad such as Walter
Felsenstein at Komische Oper. He was especially impressed by Gotz
Friedrich and worked as an assistant to Swedish director Ingmar
Bergman.
   In 1974, he successfully directed his first opera in Vadstena in
southern Sweden. He worked in Gelsenkirchen in West Germany and in
1977 he made his debut at the Stockholm Opera, which was a critical
success.
   At the time of his death, he was working with an opera by
Richard Strauss in Antwerp, Belgium, and the first performance of
Finnish composer Einojuhani Rautavaara's opera ``Vincent'' in
Helsinki.
</TEXT>
