<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0708 12-01 0775</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0708,0798</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Kill 4 Members of Underground Palestinian Group</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS one graf for 2nd pvs `The army...' to CORRECT wounded from
four to three, one graf for 13th pvs `Palestinian sources' to ADD name
of a third victim, 6 grafs for final graf with quotes from jailed Palestinian</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers disguised as Arabs killed four
members of a Palestinian gang Friday in a barber shop shootout in
Nablus, the occupied West Bank's largest city, Arab journalists
reported.
   The army confirmed soldiers killed four members of an
organization known as the Black Panthers and wounded three, who
were captured. It said there were no casualties among the soldiers.
   Street battles broke out after the shooting and the army barred
Jewish settlers from the area, according to witnesses and police
reports. Hospital officials said five Palestinians were wounded in
the clashes.
   Israeli soldiers or settlers have killed at least 623
Palestinians since an uprising began two years ago in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip, and 42 Israelis have died. At least 154
alleged collaborators with the Israelis have been killed by other
Palestinians.
   Friday's army raid was the second on radical Palestinian groups
in Nablus in less than a month. It followed warnings by military
officials of a campaign against gangs blamed for killing alleged
collaborators.
   Israel radio said the head of Israel's Shin Bet security service
told officials 500 Palestinian guerrilla squads had been counted
during the uprising.
   It said the Shin Bet chief, whose name is an official secret,
gave the assessment Thursday. He was quoted as saying 170 of the
groups were linked to the Fatah faction of Palestine Liberation
Organization chairman Yasser Arafat and were uncovered since Arafat
publicly renounced terrorism a year ago.
   Witnesses in Nablus said soldiers wearing Arab robes and
Palestinian headscarves arrived at the entrance to the Old City in
a red Mercedes with West Bank license plates.
   Seven men got out and fired into a barber shop about 40 yards
from the Ajaj Mosque, said a witness who identified himself only as
Nezar.
   He said soldiers later carried several bodies out of the shop on
stretchers. An Arab journalist said hundreds of shots were heard.
   An official army statement said soldiers confronted Palestinians
armed with an M-16 assault rifle and several pistols, and opened
fire.
   An Arab doctor who arrived with an ambulance to pick up the
injured said an Israeli army officer told him: ``You are not going
to take any casualties. ... I killed all the Black Panthers.''
   Palestinian sources identified two victims as Black Panther
members Imad Nasser, Hani Tayem and Omar Arafat _ all 22. The name
of the other victim was not available.
   According to the army, the Black Panthers have killed 16
Palestinians on suspicion of cooperation with Israel.
   Although the group once was linked to Fatah, it is said to have
carried out killings in violation of Arafat's orders.
   Members of the group were seen in Nablus minutes after the Nov.
23 shooting death of a 35-year-old woman as a suspected
collaborator. One showed a reporter a bulging grayish-green bag and
said it contained an M-16.
   The army imposed a curfew on Nablus and nearby refugee camps
Friday, ordering about 120,000 residents to stay indoors.
   On two major West Bank road junctions leading to Nablus,
soldiers and police stopped hundreds of vehicles carrying Jewish
settlers home and told them the roads were not safe, according to
police reports.
   Israeli journalists said Palestinians built stone barricades and
hurled firebombs and rocks on many roads around Nablus.
   It was the most serious confrontation in Nablus since Nov. 9,
when soldiers killed a youth said to be a leader of a gang called
the Red Eagles, and captured four of its members.
   In an interview from prison on Israel television, one of the
captured Red Eagles said he murdered collaborators ``to purify''
Palestinian society.
   Jabber Hawash, 17, said he participated in eight murders,
including the axing of his cousin, a middle-aged woman.
   He said the Red Eagles interrogated 140 suspects, sometimes
beating Arabs who refused t answer questions.
   The interrogations and slayings, he said, were sometimes in
defiance of PLO orders to end the killings.
   ``If we stop the killing, what can we do here, just sit
around?'' he said. Israel radio said the latest collaborator killed
was Nimer Abu Rabiya, 33, of Khan Yunis in the Gaza Strip. It said
he was found dead in Ketziot prison Friday and a 23-year-old
Palestinian inmate said he killed Rabiya because the victim was an
informer, the radio said.
</TEXT>
