<FIRST>r w AM-LeathRetires     12-01 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Leath Retires,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Congressman To Retire Next Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Marvin Leath, a six-term Texas
congressman and influential member of the House Armed Services
Committee, announced Friday he would not seek re-election next year.
   Leath, 58, said he ``really can't explain'' his reasons for
retiring after a dozen years in Congress. He said he would like to
write a book and perhaps a syndicated column, while pursuing a
country music career.
   ``Though it was the most agonizing decision of my life, I
believe it is time to move along _ time for someone else to take up
the mantle; time for another citizen to accept that
responsibility,'' said Leath, a former small-town banker and high
school football coach who first won the seat in 1978.
   Leath, of Waco, is one of the Texas congressional delegation's
wealthiest members, having listed the minimum value of his assets
at $1.3 million. His decision to retire in 1990 would allow him to
convert to personal use the remaining cash in his campaign
treasury, which totaled $487,535 at the end of September, according
to records at the Federal Election Commission.
   Under ethics reform legislation just approved by Congress,
members elected before 1980 have until 1993 to retire or lose the
right to convert the cash to personal use. Leath said the new law,
however, had nothing to do with his decision to retire.
   Norm Ornstein of the American Enterprise Insitute said he was
disappointed by Leath's decision ``because there are few more
interesting or nicer people on Capitol Hill. ...''
   Ornstein said Leath has a reputation for ``providing a lot of
the glue'' that has kept the Democratic Party together, serving as
a bridge between liberal and conservative factions on defense and
budget issues.
   Now, Leath says, he wants to write continue writing country
music and approach singer Willie Nelson and say: ``Willie, it's
time these two old Waco boys did an album, and let's call it
`Willie and His Congressman.'''
</TEXT>
