<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 2250EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Children'sAds     12-01 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Children's Ads,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>ACT Asks FTC to Halt `Deceptive' Ads Aimed at Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consumer advocacy organization for children
asked the government Friday to stop television stations and several
toy manufacturers from broadcasting during children's programs
advertisements the group said are deceptive.
   In a petition to halt commercials by six toy manufacturers,
Action for Children's Television asked the Federal Trade Commission
to initiate an inquiry and regulations regarding television
advertising practices aimed at children.
   ACT accused three independent New York-area television stations
and six toy manufacturers of ``engaging in unfair and deceptive
trade practices in their presentation of product advertisements for
children's toys ... which misrepresent the nature and performance
of such products.''
   ``These things are so deceptive they could deceive adults,''
Peggy Charren, the president of ACT, said in a telephone interview.
   ``Too often we do our worst advertising and direct it at kids,''
she said.
   Charren began ACT in 1968 to encourage informative children's
television programming and to monitor advertising aimed at
children. The group is funded by its 10,000 members nationwide and
other private donations.
   Charren said the group had seen vast improvements in children's
ads during the 1970s but began to see a recurrence of earlier
problems in the 1980s because of the deregulatory policies of the
Reagan adminstration and the rapid advancement of television
production technology.
   Named in the petition were WPIX-TV, WNYW-TV and New Jersey-based
WWOR-TV.
   Spokesmen for the stations said they had not been contacted by
the FTC concerning ACT's petition.
   However, Ted Faraone of WNYW said his station ``does screen
commercials very carefully, particularly those aimed at children to
screen out anything which is deceptive.''
   ``It's the kind of thing that we are very sensitive to,'' said
Ellen Morgenstern of WWOR-TV.
   ``It is not a problem that is unique to these stations,'' said
Peggy Charren, the president of ACT, in a telephone interview.
   But Charren said she was encouraged because any rules or
policies the government applied to the stations named in the
petition would apply to all stations.
   Toy commercials cited by ACT include: Ring Raiders by Matchbox
Toys, Galoob Toys' Micro Machine Service City, Mattel's Food
Fighters, Hasbro's Pogo Ball, Toy Biz's Flip Ball and Milton
Bradley's Guess Who game.
   The Ring Raiders commercial ``shows airplanes flying free when
in fact they stay attached to a child's hand'' and the Galoob spot
``shows a city complete with cars and trucks, when in fact the
product includes no vehicles,'' ACT said.
   The group acknowledged that Galoob includes a disclaimer saying
vehicles are sold separately but said ``this message is totally
ineffective with children who cannot read.''
   The Ring Raiders and Micro Machine Service City spots also are
critcized in a Consumer Reports television special on children's
advertising scheduled to air next week on Home Box Office.
   ``We do not believe the commercials are deceptive in any way,''
said Steve Klein, executive vice president and general counsel for
Galoob.
   Galoob has sold more than 55 million Micro Machine vehicles and
playsets in the three years since they hit the market, said Klein,
adding that none of the toys had been returned because of consumer
dissatisfaction due to deceptive advertising.
   Klein also said a survey conducted by an independent company
using a Micro Machine commercial similar to the one ACT finds
objectionable showed the ad ``was cleary understood by children.''
   ``There was no confusion. The filming techniques were fully
comprehended,'' Klein said of the group of boys aged 6-10 who
participated in the survey.
   Michele Litzky, a spokeswoman for Matchbox, said the firm's
advertising is produced in accordance with guidelines of the
Children's Advertising Review Unit of the Better Business Bureau.
   Glenn Bozart, spokesman for Mattel, said the company could not
respond because officials had not seen details of the petition.
   Efforts to reach other manufacturers cited by ACT were
unsuccessful.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891201-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 2301EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     12-01 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Calls Nicaragua's Refusal of Visas `Insult'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States on Friday denounced
as an ``insult'' Nicaragua's refusal to grant visas to a 20-member
delegation appointed by President Bush to observe the Feb. 25
general elections.
   The Foreign Ministry said in a communique Thursday that such a
delegation would not be impartial, declaring:
   ``From the point of view of his credibility before us, the very
fact that Mr. Bush has been the one to appoint this commission is
enough for it to be totally discredited.''
   State Department Deputy Spokesman Richard Boucher replied Friday:
   ``The denial of visas ... is merely one more illustration of
what the Sandinistas say and what they do. Refusing visas to this
prestigious delegation co-chaired by Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind.,
and Rep. Tony Beilenson, D-Calif., is an insult to their
integrity.''
   Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government invited dozens of
world observers to supervise the elections, including delegations
from the United Nations, the Organization of American States and
the European Parliament.
   The ministry said these organizations and individuals are
experienced, honest and impartial, but ``the same, unfortunately,
cannot be said of President Bush, nor, therefore, of any commission
appointed by him to observe the elections in Nicaragua.''
   It said a U.S. congressional vote Wednesday to continue
non-lethal aid to Nicaraguan rebels ``will allow the Contras to
keep infiltrating ... into Nicaragua to assassinate our people and
create confusion in the electoral process.''
   It complained about $9 million approved by Congress in October
to aid the campaign of Violeta Barrios de Chamorro, the
presidential candidate of the 14-party United National Opposition,
the strongest challenger to the governing Sandinista National
Liberation Front.
   The communique said, ``There exists a clear incompatibility
between pretending to buy the election of a candidate while at the
same time pretending to be accepted as impartial observers in our
elections.''
   Boucher said in Washington:
   ``Just two weeks ago the ... Foreign Ministry indicated to the
administration that the government of Nicaragua welcomed the
establishment of this delegation and that it intended to issue the
visas.
   ``The government of Nicaragua raised no question of linkage
between their visas and other issues.''
   He complained that Nicaragua ``professes to support Esquipulas
and the Tela accords'' _ regional peace agreements signed by
Nicaragua and other Central American nations _ ``but it provides
arms to El Salvador's FMLN, including advanced surface-to-air
missiles.''
   A small plane carrying 25 surface-to-air missiles crashed
Saturday in El Salvador. El Salvador said the plane and its four
crew, all of whom died, were Nicaraguan, and broke diplomatic
relations with Managua. It said the missiles were for the rebel
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, or FMLN.
   Boucher said that while Nicaragua promises an open and fair
election and talks peace, it ``suspended the cease-fire and stepped
up the intimidation of voters in addition to denying access to some
observers ... and has increased its troop buildup along the
Honduran border.''
   ``The Sandinistas can't have it both ways. The U.S. continues to
believe that the holding of free and fair elections under
international monitoring is an important opportunity to resolve the
conflict in Nicaragua and to improve relations with the United
States.''
   He said the decision to the visas ``certainly raises questions
about whether ... Nicaragua shares this belief.
   ``Moreover, the United States has made it clear that if the
elections are deemed free and fair it will recognize and respect
the outcome.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
