<FIRST>r i AM-Flight103     12-01 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detectives Apply to Seize Arab's Clothing in Bomb Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA JANZON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UPPSALA, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police asked a court Friday to approve
the seizure of 15 bags of clothing by Scottish detectives
investigating the explosion of Pan Am Flight 103 nearly a year ago.
   The clothing was taken Monday from the home of Mohammed Abo
Talb, a Palestinian being tried on charges related to bombings in
Scandinavia and Holland in 1985 and 1986.
   Seven Swedish policemen and three Scottish investigators
stripped the apartment of clothing, emptying the closets of Abo
Talb's entire family, said his ex-wife, who still lives with him.
   Abo Talb, a member of the Palestine Popular Struggle Front, was
linked to Flight 103 when he was found to have been in Malta two
months before the bombing Dec. 21, 1988.
   Reports say investigators traced clothing bought in Malta to the
suitcase containing the bomb that blew the jetliner apart over
Lockerbie, Scotland, killing 270 people.
   Detectives searched Abo Talb's apartment in Uppsala for clothing
purchased in Malta that could link him to the disaster.
   In a 15-minute hearing, Prosecutor Ulf Forsberg asked the court
to declare confiscation of the clothing legal. Foreign police
cannot seize evidence from a resident of Swedish without court
approval, and must prove its value to their investigation.
   The judge said he would decide by Monday. He asked reporters not
to give his name, because ``we don't want to be prey on the
streets.''
   Forsberg said in the hearing that Abo Talb was ``a suspect in
another case in another country,'' but the Lockerbie crash was not
mentioned specifically.
   Abo Talb was brought from a Stockholm jail to Uppsala, 40 miles
to the north, for a closed hearing that followed the open session.
   Jamila Mograbi, Abo Talb's former wife, told reporters she was
questioned for an hour during the search by the 10 Swedish and
Scottish policemen on Monday, and was called to the police station
Wednesday for four hours of further interrogation.
   She said the officers took away 15 large plastic bags of
clothing, and her family had to borrow clothes from friends.
Although she is divorced from Abo Talb, she is pregnant with their
third child.
   Ms. Mograbi said Abo Talb had not left Sweden in November or
December of 1988 and she could prove his whereabouts on at least
several days during those months.
   According to his passport, Abo Talb was in Malta for a week in
October 1988. He told his lawyer he went there on business.
   His ex-wife, the sister of two other defendants in Abo Talb's
bombing trial, said he went to Malta to recover from a knife wound.
She did not say how he was wounded.
   ABC television reported Thursday the Flight 103 bomb was built
by three terrorists who had spent nine years in Israeli prisons for
an unsuccessful attempt to blow up an Israeli El Al airliner in
Nairobi, Kenya.
   It said they were recruited by Ahmed Jibril, leader of the
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command.
   Abo Talb's Popular Struggle Front and Jibril's group belong to
the so-called rejectionist front opposing Yasser Arafat, chairman
of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
</TEXT>
