<FIRST>r w AM-EconomicSummit     12-01 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economic Summit,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Annual Meeting Will Be In Houston In July</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House on Friday officially announced
that Houston will be the site of a seven-nation economic summit
meeting July 9-11.
   The international gathering of the world's seven richest
industrial states is held annually, with the location rotated among
Canada, Japan, Great Britain, France, United States, Germany and
Italy.
   President Bush assigned Fred Malek, an official in his 1988
presidential campaign and the manager of his operation at last
year's Republican National Convention, to be director of the summit.
   Malek is president of Northwest Airlines and co-chairman of the
Coldwell Banker Commercial Group.
   The White House said Richard T. McCormack, the undersecretary of
state for economic and agricultural affairs, will be Bush's
personal representative for policy at the summit.
   Bush had said earlier that he wanted the summit to be in his
adoptive home state of Texas and that the decision was between San
Antonio and Houston.
</TEXT>
