<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 2144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PentagonProbe     12-01 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon Probe,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Consultant Gets Six-Month Sentence</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP _ A defense consultant was sentenced Friday
to serve six months in a work-release facility for selling
confidential bid information on a $100 million Pentagon contract to
Unisys Corp.
   U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton in Alexandria, Va., ordered
William J. Sanda to serve the six-month sentence in a community
facility where he would be released each day to go to work.
   Sanda, 53, was also ordered to serve two years of supervised
probation following completion of the six-month term for conspiring
to defraud the government.
   Sanda pleaded guilty to the conspiracy charge Sept. 2, admitting
that he sold confidential bid information on a $100 million Marine
Corps electronics contract to Unisys Corp. for $24,750 and split
the proceeds with a fellow consultant.
   Sanda, who was president Strategic Systems Institute of
Rockville, Md., is now cooperating with the Justice Department's
continuing investigation of defense procurement fraud that is
nicknamed ``Operation Ill Wind.''
   In pleading guilty earlier this fall, Sanda admitted that in
March 1987 he agreed to serve as ``front man'' for fellow
consultant William Parkin. Sanda and Parkin shared the proceeds of
the fees Unisys paid for the information obtained from the Pentagon.
   Parkin, 65, has been sentenced to 26 months in prison and fined
$25,000.
   Parkin is also cooperating with the investigation.
</TEXT>
