<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 2145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-World-AIDS     12-01 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-World-AIDS,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swedes Call for Legalizing Homosexual Marriage to Combat AIDS</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Art-Aids, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE FAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Swedish authorities observed World AIDS Day on Friday with a
call for legal homosexual marriage, and other countries introduced
weapons against the disease that ranged from free syringes to a
cartoon series.
   In Geneva, the World Health Organization, which was sponsoring
the day to raise awareness of the epidemic, displayed a patchwork
quilt at its headquarters carrying names of victims claimed by the
disease.
   Claes Ortendahl, director of Sweden's Social Welfare Board, said
legalizing of homosexual marriage would help suppress the disease
by discouraging promiscuity.
   Homosexuals and intravenous drug users are among the
highest-risk groups for AIDS, which destroys the body's ability to
fight infection.
   Cyprus began a weeklong series of television cartoons presenting
information about AIDS and how to prevent it.
   ``The campaign is dedicated to the island's youth, because they
are most vulnerable to the deadly disease,'' said Dr. Haris Fessas
of the island's National AIDS Committee.
   A Gallup poll released Friday found 73 percent of Canadian
teen-agers interviewed and 64 percent of adults believe condom
dispensing machines should be installed in high schools to protect
schoolchildren.
   ``The potential for the movement of the AIDS epidemic into the
youth population is very high,'' said Robert Burr, the Canadian
health association's communications director.
   Soviet lawmaker Boris Yeltsin, on a six-day unofficial visit to
Greece, announced he would give 1 million disposable syringes to
Soviet children's hospitals.
   Yeltsin said most Soviet hospitals have re-usable syringes,
increasing the risk of contracting AIDS.
   Full-page newspaper advertisements in Britain pointed out that
it is impossible to say exactly how many people are infected
because a person can carry the AIDS virus for years without showing
symptoms.
   ``We know of 11,218 people in the United Kingdom who have been
infected with the virus that leads to AIDS. It's the number we
don't know that is even more worrying,'' said the advertisements
paid for by the British Health Education Authority.
   Many countries do not report figures of AIDS victims because of
poor reporting facilities or for fear of losing face and suffering
bad publicity that could damage tourism.
   In Vietnam, state radio said authorities found no one carrying
the AIDS virus when they tested 6,500 people from high-risk groups
in Hanoi and three other cities.
   Vietnam, China and many other nations consider AIDS a foreign
threat.
   In Sydney, Australia, the Morning Herald newspaper said the
disease had claimed the lives of 10 ``great artists' from Australia
and published their photographs under the headline ``The Killer
that is Gathering In Our Best and Our Brightest.''
   ``Today, with the (death) toll well over 800, and 10,000
Australians known to be infected, artists and performers fear we
are going the same way as the United States,'' the newspaper said.
   Updating its AIDS report Friday, the World Health Organization
said 11,000 new cases were registered by last month, bringing the
total reported 198,165.
   The United States has reported more than 110,000 of the cases.
More than 66,000 people have died of AIDS in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
