<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Crash 1stLd-Writethru a0698 12-01 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0698,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Army Helicopter Crashes; Pilot Killed, Crewman Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with night-vision goggles being tested
when crash occurred, details. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WUERZBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Army helicopter on night
maneuvers crashed in a field near here, killing the pilot and
injuring the other crewman aboard, the Army said Friday.
   The accident occurred late Thursday while the OH-58C helicopter
was on a training exercise, according to the 3rd Infantry Division
based in Wuerzburg.
   Rep. Frank McCloskey, D-Ind., a member of the House Armed
Services Committee, said in Washington that the Army informed him
the crash took place during a night-vision goggles mission.
   ``I am convinced that these tragic accidents will continue until
Army officials admit that they have a problem and totally rewrite
their night-vision goggles program,'' McCloskey said in a statement.
   McCloskey, who favors a temporary suspension of the goggles, has
called for a coordinated Pentagon investigation and a review of the
military use of the goggles, which amplify low light.
   Critics have questioned whether the goggles work adequately when
there is no moon or when cloudy weather obscures stars.
   The Army said the helicopter struck a cable attached to a
high-tension wire pylon and crashed in a field about six miles
northeast of Wuerzburg.
   Both crewmembers were flown to the 60th Evacuation Hospital in
Wuerzburg, where the pilot was pronounced dead. The other crewman
was taken to the University Hospital in Wuerzburg, where he was
listed in fair condition, the statement said.
   Neither was identified.
   The helicopter was assigned to the 4th Brigade (Aviation) at
Giebelstadt Army Airfield, the statement said.
   Wuerzburg is about 75 miles southeast of Frankfurt. Giebelstadt
is just south of Wuerzburg.
   The Orange County Register newspaper in California reported last
March that since 1978, 37 of 41 Army helicopter crashes in which
night goggles were used occurred when there was not enough
moonlight for the devices to amplify. It said those crashes killed
65 soldiers.
</TEXT>
