<DOCNO> AP891201-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 2341EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Guyana     12-01 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guyana,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Guyana Replaces Haiti as Hemisphere's Poorest Nation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team that assessed Guyana's economy
said the former British colony has replaced Haiti as the poorest
nation in the Western Hemisphere.
   The team was led by Alister Mcintyre, secretary-general of the
Caribbean Community. In a 32-page report relesed Thursday, it said
Guyana should try to attract foreign investment through joint
ventures and by selling state companies.
   Mcintyre's group generally agreed with austerity measures
required by the International Monetary Fund, including a recent
devaluation of the Guyana dollar, now worth 3 cents U.S. cents; a
cut in government spending, and efforts to reduce the $2 billion
foreign debt.
   The IMF required the actions as conditions for financing a $1
billion recovery program aimed at reorganizing the stagnant,
state-dominated economy, which has shown no growth in 10 years.
   According to the report, bauxite, sugar, rice and other exports
have fallen 20 percent below levels in the 1970s and ``Guyana is
now ranked below Haiti as the poorest country in the Western
Hemisphere.''
   ``Productive assets are in a state of disrepair,'' it said.
``Nutrition and health standards have fallen sharply.'' The
investigators, who spent a week in the country on South America's
northeastern shoulder, said the gross national product had declined
6 percent a year since 1980.
   Skilled professionals have emigrated to North America and the
Caribbean at an alarming rate because of the decline, the report
said.
   ``Recent estimates put emigration at 1,000 per month, or about 3
percent of the working age population per annum,'' it said.
</TEXT>
