<FIRST>r i AM-Angola-Bomb     12-01 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola-Bomb,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes in Luanda Apartment Building, 11 Wounded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUANDA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded Friday night in an
apartment building housing some workers for the state oil company,
wounding at least 11 people, security officials reported.
   No one asserted responsibility for the attack, but investigators
suspected U.S.-backed rebels fighting the Marxist government.
   Security officials said the bomb went off in a four-story
building in Luanda, the capital.
   ANGOP, the government news agency, said the bomb was placed
under the main stairway of the building that has apartments for
employees of the Sonangol state oil company.
   It said two of 11 people injured were in serious condition.
   Witnesses said they believed some people were injured by jumping
from windows on uppor floors because the stairway was destroyed by
the blast.
   The explosion was the fourth in Luanda in a year. Previous
targets were the state airline TAAG, U.S. and French oil companies
and a military supply center.
   The rebels claimed responsibility for two of the bombings.
   UNITA _ the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
_ has been fighting to force the government to share power since
Angola gained independence from Portugal in 1975 and Marxist forces
emerged victorious from a brief civil war.
</TEXT>
