<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 2244EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Crowd     12-01 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Crowd,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spectators Cheer Coup Conflict</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Philippines, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people watched the
conflict Friday between rebels and loyal troops, and many cheered
when mutinous pilots attacked the presidential palace.
   Hundreds of spectators gathered on the South Superhighway
overpass as three T-28 aircraft and a Sikorsky helicopter bombarded
the palace. As the aircraft fired, people cheered.
   ``Wow! That was a great shot,'' said cigarette vendor Julio
Torres, pointing toward the palace. ``But it would really be better
if there could be a dogfight later on, just like in the movies.''
   Hours later, Philippine air force F-5 jets chased the renegade
aircraft out of the Manila area and destroyed some on the ground at
an air station in Sangley Point in Cavite province, just across
Manila Bay.
   In the afternoon, American warplanes helped patrol the skies
over the capital, with President Bush's approval, to help President
Corazon Aquino's government the sixth attempted coup. Mrs. Aquino
was not in the presidential palace when it was attacked.
   ``I wish there could be a live gun battle,'' said a 9-year-old
boy on the overpass. ``I haven't seen one, although I've watched a
lot of war movies.''
   Early Friday, rebellious marines from Fort Bonifacio seized
control of the air force headquarters in the suburban Villamor air
base.
   Soon people from squatters' districts outside the two military
compounds rushed to the overpass as rebel troops set up road blocks.
   As the officers issued orders children gathered around the
soldiers, examining their automatic weapons and recoilless rifles.
   Others tapped the sides two armored personnel carriers and two
landing- vehicle tanks and pointed at the machine guns.
   As time passed the onlookers were joined by office and factory
workers. Newspaper boys arrived and sold early editions.
   By midmorning vendors were selling soda, peanuts and boiled duck
eggs.
   Indian businessman Shiv Inder Singh, his wife and daughter posed
for souvenir photographs with rebel soldiers.
   Singh, who plans to establish a garment factory in the
Philippines, said, ``I don't think the coup will affect foreign
investments, if the government acts swiftly.'' His wife said, ``I
think this happens here all the time.''
   There have been at least six attempted coups since Mrs. Aquino
became president after President Ferdinand Marcos was ousted in a
civilian-military uprising in February 1986.
</TEXT>
