<FIRST>r a AM-People-Fonda-Hayden     12-01 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Fonda-Hayden,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jane Fonda and Tom Hayden File for Divorce</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Jane Fonda and California
Assemblyman Tom Hayden filed separate divorce petitions on Friday,
both saying the split after 16 years of marriage was amicable.
   Fonda and Hayden reached agreements on financial and property
matters, but details weren't disclosed because of a privacy pact,
their attorneys said.
   The couple separated in December 1988 and the court papers
didn't give a reason for the split. They will share custody of
their 16-year-old son, Troy, their spokesman, Stephen Rivers, said
in a statement.
   ``Tom and Jane wish each other well and look to the future with
enthusiasm and optimism,'' said Rivers.
   Attorneys said it was unusual for both parties in a divorce case
to file separate petitions.
   ``They just wanted to make it very clear that neither side was
initiating this,'' said Hayden's lawyer, Ken Young. ``They just
reached a point where they wanted to move on with their lives.''
   Attorney Dennis Wasser, representing Miss Fonda, said the
divorce would be final in six months.
   Miss Fonda, 52, won best actress Oscars for the 1971 film
``Klute'' and in 1978 for ``Coming Home.''
   Hayden, 50, the one-time Chicago Seven anti-war activist,
represents Santa Monica as a Democrat in the state Assembly.
   The two were married in January 1973.
  
</TEXT>
