<FIRST>u a AM-Nynex 1stLd-Writethru a0786 12-01 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nynex, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0786,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Striking Nynex Workers Approve Contract</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to clarify in strike was nearly 4 months,
UPDATE with Nynex comment; picks up 4th graf pvs: `In August ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nynex telephone workers ratified a contract
Friday after an acrimonious walkout that lasted nearly 4 months,
marking the final settlement of strikes against regional telephone
companies that began in August.
   ``It's over, it's over, it's over,'' said Bob Master, a
spokesman for the Communications Workers of America. ``We're
happy.''
   Eighty-five percent of the union workers approved the contract
in voting that began Monday and ended early Friday. The workers
planned to return to work Monday.
   ``We are very pleased,'' said Nynex spokesman John Bonomo. ``The
settlement is fair for everyone _ customers, employees and
shareholders. We're looking forward to welcoming all our employees
back to work on Monday, and dedicating ourselves to providing the
quality service our customers rely on us for.''
   In August, workers staged walkouts against four of the Baby Bell
companies formed in the break-up of AT&amp;T _ Nynex, Pacific Telesis,
Ameritech and Bell Atlantic. All except Nynex were back at work by
the end of the month.
   At Nynex, the CWA's 40,000 regional members struck subsidiary
New York Telephone on Aug. 6. They were joined at New England
Telephone by 20,000 members of the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers.
   A Nynex spokesman did not immediately return a telephone message
seeking comment.
   The rancorous strike left one striker dead after a picket line
confrontation and the telephone companies with a backlog on new
installations.
   The major issue concerned the company's insistence that workers
share part of their health costs. The final settlement did not
include any health-cost sharing.
   The IBEW settled first; its workers returned to work more than
two weeks ago. The CWA reached a tentative agreement on Nov. 22.
However, negotiations with two constituent groups continued until
Wednesday, Master said.
</TEXT>
