<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1343EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv04   12-01 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv04,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Monday, Dec. 4</HEAD>
<HEAD>When `Bad' News Is Welcome</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The strange ways of Wall Street were put on
exhibit again last week when a spate of reports from government and
the private sector showed the economy was continuing to weaken.
   Prices rose.
   Or, perhaps it was the strange ways of the Federal Reserve that
were on display because, it can be argued, the Fed also reacted
somewhat strangely to the developing ``bad'' news.
   That news was relentless. Consumer spending, two-thirds of the
gross national product, fell. Automobile sales dropped. Housing
starts were off from a year earlier, helping to bring down spending
on furniture and appliances, too.
   The index of leading economic indicators fell 0.4 percent in
October. The November report from the National Association of
Purchasing Management also suggested contraction in manufacturing.
Initial jobless claims rose.
   News of that sort, piling up as it does, indicates impending
recession. Most recessions are accompanied by strains on corporate
profits, and profit, in in the final analysis, is the basis of
stock prices.
   But the stock market rose on the news.
   There was, however, no mystery to why it rose _ it rose because
the big professional portfolio managers convinced themselves that
all the negative news would force the Federal Reserve to let
interest rates drop.
   Even though the Fed sent a strong signal to the contrary by
propping up the federal funds rate _ the overnight rate for loans
between banks _ it wasn't believed. Eventually, it was reasoned,
the Fed had to let up on restraint.
   Consider some of the other evidence:
   Domestic auto sales since the end of the third quarter were 15
percent below the pace for the first nine months of 1989. Plants
have been shut down and workers have been laid off.
   The growth of U.S. exports has slowed. New orders for durable
goods fell 0.6 percent in October, the fourth decline in six
months. Production of goods such as food, clothing and paper are
off from a year ago.
   The weight of evidence, the market said, demanded action by the
Fed. But so far as can be determined from published statements, Fed
Chairman Alan Greenspan, hasn't changed his mind about inflation
being his primary concern.
   The market doesn't believe him.
   Early last week, word spread through the big investment centers
that the Fed would force down short-term rates in an effort to slow
or reverse the slump in manufacturing. In fact, the Fed did inject
reserves into the banking system.
   One day later it indicated differently, when it jacked up the
federal funds rate.
   The Fed still has reasons to be concerned. The jobless rate is
low by recent standards and that could force wages higher. And the
0.5 percent rise in the October consumer price index annualizes to
more than 6 percent.
   In the securities markets, however, they discount such data,
contending that the jobless rate will rise and the price index will
soon fall if the Fed doesn't give the economy a lift. Nothing does
it, they say, like lower rates.
   In effect, the market seemed to say, this is as bad as it gets.
But has the market properly assessed the Fed chairman, who is
determined to end inflation, once and for all?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Monday, Dec. 4.</NOTE>
</DOC>
