<DOCNO> AP891201-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:IraqiMusic Adv07   12-01 0847</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Iraqi Music, Adv 07,0871</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday AMs, Dec. 7, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Iraqi Maestro Bridges Culture Gap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Munir Bashir is known as the ``emir of the
oud.''
   He uses the pear-shaped stringed instrument to promote Arabic
music around the world, and to bridge a culture gap. But he
believes that one of his biggest tasks in life is to instill a love
of Arabic music among youngsters who have been seduced by Western
rock and disco music and preserve a rich artistic heritage.
   ``It's a shame,'' he said in an interview. ``We have such great
music, but the younger generations never heed it.''
   Bashir, a native of Mosul in northern Iraq, said that for Arabs
to neglect their traditional music is to ignore an important aspect
of their cultural identity.
   ``Music is part of the cultural identity of any people. It's not
something you can borrow from others,'' he said. ``Music is not
just entertainment. It's a source of spiritual and moral
uplifting.''
   Bashir, 59, believes Arabic music is now in a state of crisis,
which he attributes to ``cultural backwardness.''
   As director of musical affairs at the Culture Ministry in
Baghdad, he has devoted 16 years to promoting Arabic music as part
of Iraq's educational system and culture.
   Bashire established a ballet and music school for children to
study and learn to play instruments and the Iraqi Institute of
Melody Studies for teen-agers.
   Three years ago, he formed the al-Bayariq ensemble, a 28-member
youth group, to develop young people's interest in authentic Arabic
music and to help preserve centuries-old songs that have begun to
disappear because of the ``ugly thrust'' of modern music. It is led
by his youngest son, Omer, 20.
   ``It's not just a source of pride, but an investment in our
cultural future,'' Bashir said. ``If we don't encourage young
people to play these instruments, our traditional music will die
and these instruments will only be found in museums.''
   Al-Bayariq brings together the oud, qanun, santur and joza, all
stringed instrumemnts, as well as the tablah, a small drum, and the
riqq, a frame drum with jingles akin to a tambourine.
   The oud is a six-stringed instrument, shaped like a lute. Bashir
believes the oud originated in Iraq. The instrument has been seen
on stone carvings dating back 2,000 years. From Arabia, the oud
made its way to Europe, possibly in the Moorish conquest of Spain,
and from it evolved the lute.
   The qanun is a zither-like instrument. The violin-like joza has
only one string that gives a strong, high pitch. It is played
resting on the leg rather than nestling under the chin. The santure
is something like a qanun, but its strings are played with sticks
rather than a bow.
   The instruments used by the ensemble are specially made for the
group by elderly craftsmen in a workshop set up by Bashir.
   The ensemble has performed in several foreign countries,
including France, and all over the Arab world. In Paris, the
youngsters performed at the Arab World Institute to standing
ovations.
   ``Now we've built a solid base, I hope these kids will stick to
their instruments, pioneering the way for others to follow,''
Bashir said.
   Arabic music has largely been ignored in the West because of its
complex melodies and ornamental flourishes that make it difficult
to grasp. But artists such as Bashir are increasingly bridging the
cultural gap.
   Critics hail him as a creative and supreme master of his
instrument, whose music springs from the authentic tradition of
Arabian music. Foreign critics say Bashir is notable for being able
to project the emotions of Arabic music, often lost to the
occidential ear, to non-Arabs.
   ``He stretches the understanding of music to the limit,'' one
European critic wrote. ``To listen to him takes as much
intellectual energy and attention as listening to the discourse of
a sage.''
   His playing is rooted in classical Arab forms but is largely
improvisational. Some critics have found it resembles progressive
jazz in many ways.
   Bashir has elevated the oud to solo instrument status after
centuries of having been used to accompany Arab singers. For one
thing, he added six more strings, pairing them with the others, to
produce a fuller sound and melodic flexibility.
   He discovered his gift for music when he was 6 years old while
listening to his mother singing lullabies to his younger brothers.
She also played several traditional instruments.
   ``She was my first idol. She breathed the love of music into
me,'' he said.
   His father made ouds and Bashir's brother also plays the
instrument.
   In his ministry office, crowded with musical instruments,
records and tapes, he spends two to three hours a day playing. No
one is allowed to interrupt him.
   ``All telephone calls and appointments have to be put off when
al-istath (the master) is playing, until he finishes his solo
performance in his office,'' said his secretary, Nizar Jawad, who
is also a lyricist and musician.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thursday AMs, Dec. 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
