<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 0925EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-InvestmentFund     12-01 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Investment Fund,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salomon Brothers Sues State, Saying It Can't Have Both Ways</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salomon Brothers Inc. filed a $150
million countersuit against West Virginia in federal court as the
state settled for $2 million a claim with a second investment
banker group.
   The separate legal actions involve in over the loss of $279
million in the state's consolidated investment fund in 1987-89,
when the fund's assets were traded on Wall Street.
   The state sued Salomon, County NatWest Government Securities
Inc. and three other firms in October, blaming them for the massive
losses suffered by the fund.
   Salomon Brothers, in a countersuit filed Thursday in U.S.
District Court in Charleston, said West Virginia wants the
brokerage house to pay for the losses, while giving the state the
profits, which it estimates at $150 million.
   It said in the suit that the state, however, cannot it have both
ways.
   ``This `heads we win, tails you lose' approach to the parties'
long-settled transactions is unconscionable, inequitable and
unjust,'' the suit contended.
   Attorney General Roger Tompkins said Salomon's suit is just one
of many countersuits against the state.
   ``All four of those defendants have filed lawsuits against the
state of West Virginia and the Board of Investments... . We're
talking millions and millions of dollars.'' Tompkins said.
   The Board of Investments, which oversees the fund, cleared one
of the defendants from further litigation Thursday.
   It voted to accept a $2 million settlement offer from County
NatWest.
   Tompkins said the settlement is significant because by settling,
County NatWest agreed that it was responsible in part for the
damages.
   ``They were willing to confess they had a problem and pay some
money to get out of this lawsuit,'' Tompkins said.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891201-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 0954EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EuropeanThemeParks     12-01 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-European Theme Parks,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Universal City' Theme Park Near London Proposed by MCA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thrill rides through a
laser-filled ``Ghostbusters'' scene and into outer space aboard a
bicycle with ``E.T.: The Extraterrestrial'' are part of a planned
$3 billion MCA Inc. theme park near London.
   The park, described in a planning application submitted to
British authorities Monday, is similar to another MCA amusement
park complex recently proposed for a site outside Paris.
   MCA will develop only one of the European sites. Officials hope
to open the new park in 1994.
   The entertainment company that operates the famed Universal
Studios tour here plans to spend $1 billion to build the park and a
studio, with additional development later to expand and erect a
hotel.
   MCA also is developing studio theme parks in Florida and Japan.
   ``We will choose which of the two to develop in March or April
of next year,'' Anthony Young, president of the MCA Enterprises
International unit, said Thursday in a telephone call from London.
   The MCA proposal adds pressure to negotiations surrounding the
French site and opens a new front in global theme park wars.
   Media conglomerates led by the Disney Co. want to cash in on
worldwide demand for U.S. entertainment at a time when more people
enjoy prosperity and greater leisure time.
   Disney is developing parks in France and Japan and is doubling
the size of its new Disney-MGM Studio Tour in Florida because it is
so popular.
   Kirk Kerkorian, through his MGM Grand Inc., hopes to open a $700
million studio theme park-hotel in Las Vegas in 1992.
   And Warner Bros. has expressed interest in building an
Australian park featuring its cartoon characters such as Bugs Bunny
and the Road Runner.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
