<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1020EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     12-01 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0325</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market opened higher today amid
optimism over the prospects for lower interest rates and ahead of
this weekend's U.S.-Soviet summit.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 8.96 points to
2,715.23 at 10 a.m. EST, 30 minutes after the opening bell.
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by about 9 to 5 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 629 issues up, 333 down and 496
unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 26.79 million
shares.
   Analysts said the market was feeling optimistic about this
weekend's summit between President Bush and Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev in Malta.
   ``Usually markets do well prior to summits,'' said Larry
Wachtel, analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. ``I don't
know what the market expects. But there's always a gamble that
something good will come out of it.''
   Investors also felt good about the prospects for lower interest
rates as new economic indictors suggest a slowdown in
fourth-quarter economic growth, observers said.
   The government reported today that its chief economic
forecasting gauge, the Index of Leading Economic Indicators, fell
0.4 percent in October, the sixth month of declines or no gain this
year.
   Though the October drop was in line with most economists'
expectation, it confirmed other data pointing to sluggish growth.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 0.73 to 192.03.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was up
0.55 to 374.39.
   On Thursday, the Dow Jones Industrial average rose 17.49 points
to 2,706.27.
   Advancing issues outpaced decliners by about 4 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
837 issues up, 629 down and 516 unchanged.
   Big Board volume came to 153.20 million shares, up from 147.27
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
