<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 11am,0368</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose sharply in brisk trading today
amid optimistic prospects for lower interest rates and ahead of
this weekend's U.S.-Soviet summit.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 21.33 points to
2,727.60 at 11 a.m. EST. The blue-chip indicator was up 8.96 points
an hour earlier.
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by about 9 to 5 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 786 issues up, 435 down and 521
unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 58.46 million
shares.
   Analysts said the market was feeling optimistic about this
weekend's summit between President Bush and Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev in Malta.
   ``Usually markets do well prior to summits,'' said Larry
Wachtel, analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. ``I don't
know what the market expects. But there's always a gamble that
something good will come out of it.''
   Analysts said the market also got a boost from economic reports
that showed the economy is continuing to slow in the fourth
quarter, reflecting hopes that the Federal Reserve will cut
short-term interest rates to stimulate growth.
   The government reported today that its chief economic
forecasting gauge, the Index of Leading Economic Indicators, fell
0.4 percent in October, the sixth month of declines or no gain this
year.
   Though the October drop was in line with most economists'
expectation, it added weight to other data that point to sluggish
growth, including the Association of Purchasing Management's
November index. That index fell to 46.6 percent from 47.6 percent
in October. A reading below 50 percent indicates a contraction in
the nation's manufacturing sector.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 1.34 to 192.64.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was at
374.42, up 0.58.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Philip Morris was up [
to 42{, General Electric had advanced | to 62| and Chevron was up {
to 69[.
   L.A. Gear was down 2} to 33\, Windmere was off 1~ to 9\ and
Great Western Financial was unchanged at 18[.
