<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Jaguar 1stLd-Writethru   12-01 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Jaguar, 1st Ld-Writethru,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jaguar Shareholders Pave Way For Ford Deal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Ford comments, picking up
in the 4th graf pvs: In response ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jaguar PLC, which is being acquired by Ford Motor
Co. in a friendly $2.5 billion deal, said Friday its shareholders
have approved lifting a restriction limiting holdings in the
British luxury auto maker to just 15 percent.
   The shareholders approved waiving the restriction by more than
99 percent. The measure required approval of at least 75 percent.
   The approval was widely expected and clears the way for Ford to
buy more Jaguar shares and gain control of its target.
   Ford spokesman Rex Greenslade said from the No. 2 U.S.
automaker's headquarters in Dearborn, Mich., that the company was
pleased with the vote.
   He said Ford planned to acquire more than 50 percent of Jaguar
stock by Dec. 8, one week after the shareholders' decision.
Considering the strength of Friday's vote, it appeared likely that
Ford, which currently owns about 13 percent of Jaguar, would reach
that goal.
   In response to the news, Jaguar rose 1.57 cents to $13.13 a
share on London's Stock Exchange. Ford has offered $13.35 a share
for Jaguar.
   At a special shareholders meeting, Jaguar Chairman John Egan
reiterated his belief that the British company has a good future
ahead as a ``strong, autonomous company.''
   Under terms of the agreement with Ford, Jaguar will have a
separate legal identity, its own board of directors, and will
retain its separate dealership network.
   Trade Secretary Nicholas Ridley announced on Thursday that the
takeover would not be referred to the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission.
   Ford announced the friendly bid on Nov. 2, a day after Ridley
waived the government's ``golden share.''
   The golden share, established when the government privatized the
formerly state-owned Jaguar in 1984, gives the government veto
power over any takeover and was originally designed to protect
Jaguar from being acquired until the end of 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
