<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1139EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   12-01 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Gain On Follow-Through, Summit Hopes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly
higher in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade,
reflecting follow-through buying from the previous session and
hopes for expanded trade with the Soviet Union.
   Many players expect this weekend's superpower summit to lead to
more sales of U.S. grain to the Soviet Union, which already is a
major buyer of U.S. corn and soybean meal.
   ``The nervousness and apprehension ahead of that meeting will
keep the bears at bay,'' said Richard Feltes, research director
with Refco Inc., a Chicago-based futures brokerage.
   The soybean market received additional support from news that
the Agriculture Department will donate $20 million worth of soybean
meal to Poland.
   Forecasts for continued dry weather in winter wheat growing
areas of the Great Plains helped to boost wheat prices.
   Gains were limited by the USDA's weekly grain-exports report,
which showed exports of soybeans and soybean meal lagging well
behind last year's pace.
   In early trading, wheat futures were 1{ cents to 3 cents higher
with the contract for delivery in December at $4.09} a bushel; corn
was } cent lower to 1{ cents higher with December at $2.37{ a
bushel; oats were { cent to } cent higher with December at $1.43{ a
bushel; soybeans were 1 cent lower to 1 cent higher with January at
$5.83 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were higher while pork futures were mixed on the
Chicago Board of Trade. The pork belly market appeared to be
steadying after a three-day collapse linked to lower-than-expected
belly exports.
   Live cattle futures were .02 cent to .20 cent higher with
December at 75.07 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .20
cent higher with January at 82.82 cents a pound; live hogs were .28
cent lower to .13 cent higher with December at 50.57 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .55 cent lower to .80 cent higher with
February at 58 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled lower Thursday, hogs were higher and pork
bellies were sharply lower.
</TEXT>
