<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1226EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Columbia     12-01 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Columbia,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guber, Peters Pick Attorney as Chief Operating Officer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Movie producers Peter Guber and Jon
Peters, the new co-chairmen of Columbia Pictures Entertainment
Inc., have chosen their longtime lawyer to oversee nearly all
Columbia's operations.
   The attorney, Alan J. Levine, has represented the ``Batman'' and
``Rain Man'' producers for the last decade. Levine has been a
partner in the Armstrong, Hirsch &amp; Levine firm since 1980, handling
major clients in the motion picture and television business.
   Levine's move to Columbia had been widely expected. Sony Corp.
purchased the studio in September for $3.4 billion, then bought
Guber and Peters out of their Warner Bros. production contract in a
settlement that some analysts have valued at up to $500 million.
   Levine will become president and chief operating officer of the
newly formed filmed entertainment group, which includes Columbia
Pictures, Tri-Star Pictures, Triumph Releasing, Columbia Pictures
Television, RCA-Columbia Home Video, Merv Griffin Enterprises, and
their various offshoots.
   ``The only thing left out is Loew's,'' the theater chain owned
by Columbia, said Columbia spokesman Ed Russell.
   The naming of Levine underlined the precarious status of
Columbia Pictures president Dawn Steel, brought in to replace David
Puttnam at the helm of the Columbia studio two years ago.
   Steel's departure from Columbia is expected soon, according to
two knowledgeable sources at the studio who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   She no longer is making important decisions; an example was
Columbia's purchase of the script ``Radio Flyer'' for more than $1
million Wednesday in a bidding war with Warner, which was handled
by Peters without her help.
   Steel, who has been offered an independent production contract
at Disney, did not return a call Thursday inquiring about her plans.
   Levine's compensation package was not revealed, but it is
expected to be extremely rich. Among other things, Sony's contract
with Guber and Peters allows them to divide up a $50 million lump
sum payment in five years between themselves and the three top
executives they hire.
   Guber and Peters also have been guaranteed salaries of $14
million over the next five years, a percentage of studio profits
that increases substantially if the profits are big and a stake in
the company's appreciation.
   As part of the deal sending Guber and Peters to Columbia, Warner
Bros. was given Columbia's one-third interest in The Burbank
Studios in exchange for the old MGM lot in Culver City.
   The move to Culver City will involve real estate deals that
Levine will not oversee, and Russell said he would not be involved
in any future deals Columbia undertakes in that area _ a hotel
purchase, for example.
   Levine, 42, of Beverly Hills, graduated from Hollywood High
School in 1964 and received his bachelor's and law degrees from the
University of Southern California.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
