<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1240EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-NCNBExpansion     12-01 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-NCNB Expansion,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>NCNB Plans New Loans, Branches for 1990</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top executives of the aggressive
superregional bank NCNB Texas said their plans for the coming years
include making billions of dollars worth of new loans and opening
hundreds of new branches.
   Executives quoted in Friday editions of the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram said the bank plans to open 250 new branches
throughout Texas by 1994, which will more than double the 219
branches the bank currently operates.
   ``We are part of a company that gained its reputation by being a
very aggressive leader in the Southeast,'' said Timothy Hartman,
chairman of NCNB Corp., parent company of the Dallas bank.
   ``We have raised $1.9 billion in new capital since September
1988, with $1.7 billion of that invested in NCNB Texas. That money
will provide the support to grow deposits and make new loans.''
   The bank is committed to making about $1.1 billion in mortgage
loans to about 13,000 Texans in 1990, Hartman said.
   NCNB has been criticized for cutting off credit to many longtime
customers of First RepublicBank Corp. NCNB Texas now owns and
operates First Republic's banks.
   The bank also has been criticized for not making new loans in
Texas.
   ``We think this concept that NCNB is not addressing the credit
side of the market is incorrect,'' said Jeffrey Wentworth, chairman
of the bank's West Texas region.
   ``To be able to show the market that we are in the marketplace,
we need to continue to demonstrate our commitment to making new
loans,'' he added.
   NCNB Texas President Kenneth Lewis said NCNB Texas approved
$1.59 billion in loans during the first nine months of the year,
with most of that increase coming from new commercial loans.
   The company also transferred $930 million in bad loans to its
special asset pool.
   Hartman predicted that NCNB Texas will earn just over $300
million for 1989, with net income of between $290 million and $300
million for 1990.
   The company reported net income of $244.3 million during the
first nine months of this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
