<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Marion-MerrellMerger     12-01 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Marion-Merrell Merger,0341</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Marion, Merrill Merger Approved for Third-Largest Drug Company
^By SALLY STREFF BUZBEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marion Laboratories Inc. shareholders
gave final approval Friday to a merger with a Dow Chemical Co.
subsidiary that will create the third-largest pharmaceutical
concern in the nation.
   Ewing Kauffman, who founded Marion Labs in the basement of his
home and is co-owner of the Kansas City Royals baseball team, told
shareholders at the company's annual meeting that he would stay on
as chairman emeritus of the merged company.
   Shareholders approved the issuance of 127 million new Marion
shares to Dow, which will merge Cincinnati-based Merrell Dow
Pharmaceuticals Inc. with Marion. Dow Chemical will retain a 67
percent stake in Marion.
   The new company, Marion Merrell Dow, will be based in Kansas
City. Annual revenues were estimated at $2.4 billion, and about
10,000 people were expected to be employed worldwide, said Fred W.
Lyons Jr., president and chief executive officer of Marion.
   Lyons noted that mid-sized companies were having trouble
competing in the drug industry. He added that the merger will help
Marion ``go into the 90s with a much stronger competititve position
than we went into the 80s.''
   Michael Herman, Marion's chief financial officer, told
stockholders to expect costs in the current quarter related to the
merger.
   Marion and Dow of Midland, Mich., announced merger plans July 17.
   Under the complicated agreement, Marion first sold 39 percent of
its 150 million outstanding shares to Dow at an estimated cost of
$2.2 billion.
   Dow will acquire the newly issued Marion shares by turning
Merrell Dow over to Marion and issuing a new class of securities
that provide for Dow to pay to Marion shareholders at the time
they're cashed in.
   Marion's leading drugs are Cardizem, used to treat angina and
high blood pressure, and the ulcer drug Carafate.
   Merrell Dow's main products are the antihistamine Seldane, an
anti-cholesterol drug Lorelco, the anti-smoking gum Nicorette and
Cepacol mouthwash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
