<FIRST>r f AM-Britain-Ferranti     12-01 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Ferranti,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Potential Bidders Abandon Joint Pursuit of Ferranti</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Aerospace PLC and Thomson-CSF, a French
defense contractor, said Friday they were no longer interested in
mounting a joint bid for the British electronics concern Ferranti
International Signal PLC.
   However, Thomson said it would continue to consider its options
regarding making an offer for Ferranti.
   Ferranti's shares fell the equivalent 14 cents Friday to close
at 63 cents on London's Stock Exchange.
   Ferranti has been hit in recent months by the revelation of
fraud connected with International Signal and Control Ltd., a U.S.
defense contractor Ferranti acquired in 1987.
   British Aerospace and Thomson-CSF announced Oct. 10 they were
considering making a joint offer for Ferranti.
   On Friday, British Aerospace said in a statement that ``in
reviewing the information so far made available on the Ferranti
business'' it had decided to withdraw its earlier interest.
   British Aerospace cited Ferranti's recent publication of revised
financial results for the year ending March 31 and British
Aerospace's judgment of its own ``strategic interests.''
   Ferranti revised downward its pre-tax profit for that fiscal
year to $20.6 million from $87.6 million originally reported.
   Ferranti also said it is dipping into capital and reserves in
the amount of $276.3 million after finding fraudulent contracts at
its American subsidiary.
   Earlier Friday, Ferranti announced the sale of $294 million
worth of shares to existing shareholders. The company said it would
hold a special shareholders meeting to vote on the share sale in
February.
   The share sale, which is fully underwritten by investment firms,
``greatly strengthens our financial position,'' said Ferranti
Chairman Derek Alun-Jones.
   On Thursday, Ferranti filed a lawsuit against four former
executives of its U.S. operation and five Panamanian companies
seeking the return of $198.5 million that it said was fraudulently
siphoned off.
   A writ issued in the High Court said the money was part of
$443.6 million paid out by Ferranti's British firms ISC
Technologies Ltd. and ISC London PLC from February 1984 to July
1989 for three allegedly fictitious arms contracts with companies
in Pakistan, the United Arab Emirates and China.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
