<DOCNO> AP891201-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1507EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ShippingFlags Bjt   12-01 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shipping Flags, Bjt,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merchant Shipping Industry Alarmed By Bush's Move</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The merchant shipping industry said Friday that
President Bush's decision to bar Panamanian-flag vessels from U.S.
ports could make shipowners pawns in diplomatic disputes.
   The move might interrupt free trade and prove costly and
disruptive to shipowners, industry insiders say.
   Bush's ban, announced Thursday, goes into effect Jan. 31 and is
one of various U.S. economic sanctions already in place against
Panama's leader, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   ``The principle of the thing is worrying,'' said Chris Horrocks,
secretary-general of the London-based International Chamber of
Shipping on Friday. ``Once merchant shipping starts becoming a pawn
in the political game, where will it lead?''
   A shipping executive who spoke on condition of anonymity said,
``Obviously you could get a situation where other countries come
out in a supportive way.''
   Shipowners already are scurrying to change flags because Bush's
move will have a significant impact on their trading abilities, he
said.
   Other countries could press their own grievances with their own
bans, Horrocks said.
   ``Another country might now say they will not accept a
particular flag, then yet another country might object to another
flag,'' he said.
   A country could, for example, decide to ban Liberian-registered
ships because Liberia trades with the United States, he said.
   The International Chamber of Shipping is the industry's
international trade association and is made up of national
shipowners' associations.
   Turkey has banned Cyrpiot-registered ships for about two years,
and countries at war ban typically each other's ships, Horrocks
said.
   ``This is more stark in this case because it involves the
world's major trading nation,'' Horrocks said.
   Bush's move is also unfair, he said, because ships that fly
Panama's flag but don't trade with the Central American country
will be hurt.
   ``We've never been happy with the principle that you use
merchant shipping as a political weapon,'' he said.
   In addition to switching flags, shipowners can reroute tankers.
Both options are time-consuming, inconvenient and costly, Horrocks
said.
   But more importantly, a spread of such bans could interfere with
the movement of goods. ``We've always stood for the principle of
liberalized trade,'' Horrocks said.
   Bush's ban would affect some 1,500 merchant ships of more than
1,000 gross tons that call each year in U.S. ports, according to
State Department estimates.
   Shipowners register under ``flags of convenience'' of Panama,
Liberia and Cyprus to take advantage of cheaper taxes and fees and
looser safety rules and labor laws.
   As of July 1986, more ships above 1,000 gross tons capacity flew
Panama's flag than any other flag for a total of 3,620 ships.
   The Soviet Union was in second place with 2,514 ships, and
Liberia was third with 1,852 vessels. Just 737 ships flew the
American flag.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891201-0144 </DOCNO>
