<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Lower On Late Plunge In Corn, Soybeans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices closed lower
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade in a late, technically
inspired drop.
   Wheat futures finished mixed, supported by rumors that the
Soviet Union had bid for 400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at
subsidized prices. The Soviets have about 800,000 tons of wheat
left to buy under an allocation granted under the Agriculture
Deparment's Export Enhancement Program.
   Talk of increased Soviet purchases of U.S. grain has dominated
trading ahead of this weekend's meeting between President Bush and
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
   Thursday's weekly USDA export figures showed soybean and soybean
meal shipments running behind last year's pace. But analysts said
that news had been in the market all day and was probably not to
blame for the late dive in soybeans and corn.
   ``Fundamentally, nothing has changed very much to warrant such a
big selloff,'' said Janice Kincheloe, a soybean market analyst in
Chicago with Cargill Investor Services Inc.
   At the close, wheat futures were 1 cent lower to 1 cent higher
with the contract for delivery in December at $4.08{ a bushel; corn
was } cent to 3} cents lower with December at $2.34{ a bushel; oats
were \ cent to 1{ cents lower with December at $1.43} a bushel;
soybeans were 1} cents to 6} cents lower with January at $5.76 a
bushel.
