<DOCNO> AP891201-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1647EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Economy 1stLd-Writethru f0153 12-01 0738</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0153,0756</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forecasting Gauge Down, But Little Talk of Recession</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 12th graf, `News of ...,' to UPDATE with Dow Jones activity;
ADDS 1 graf with S&amp;L activity report. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's chief economic forecasting
gauge signaled a slowdown in October, but other evidence suggested
lower interest rates will keep the economy from toppling into a
recession.
   The 0.4 percent drop in the Commerce Department's Index of
Leading Economic Indicators announced Friday fits in with the
consensus among analysts that the final quarter of this year and
the first three months of 1990 will see weak growth at best.
   ``The indicators are telling us what they'vebeen telling us for
some time and that is that the economy is continuing to expand, but
at a slow rate,'' said economist David Berson of the Federal
National Mortgage Association.
   However, he and other analysts said a number of factors
mitigated the unfavorable report. The decline followed two monthly
gains; most of the weakness was concentrated in only two of the
index's 11 forward-looking business statistics.
   And, elements of the index and a separate report on October
construction spending suggest that the Federal Reserve Board's cuts
in interest rates since June are beginning to stimulate the economy.
   Construction activity rose 1 percent in October, bolstered by
the first gain in single-family construction in nine months, the
Commerce Department said.
   Four of the 11 indicators were positive. Building permits
increased 2.8 percent and the nation's money supply, reflecting
lower interest rates, expanded modestly. Other positive signs were
a slight increase in prices of sensitive materials, indicating
increased demand, and an upturn in business capital investment.
   October's overall drop, which was expected by most economists,
followed gains of 0.3 percent in September and 0.6 percent in
August. Both gains were revised in the report to reflect a slightly
better increase than earlier reported.
   For the first 10 months of 1989, the index has fallen five
times, risen four times and remained unchanged in one month.
   The various changes left the index at 144.6 percent of its 1982
base of 100. That represents a 0.4 percent decline at an annual
rate for the year so far, compared with a 3.8 percent gain in the
first 10 months of 1988.
   ``The recent erratic fluctuations in the index are commensurate
with an economy that has slowed substantially but is not headed
over a precipice,'' said economist Gordon Richards of the National
Association of Manufacturers.
   News of the October decline helped spark a stock market rally
that put the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials ahead by 41.38
points at closing. Traders took the report as an indication the
Fed, which last nudged interest rates lower in early November,
could move again. Optimism about the U.S.-Soviet summit meeting
also contributed to the rally.
   The two biggest negatives in the index were an increase in
claims for unemployment insurance and a drop in average work week
for factory workers.
   The other weak signs were a drop in unfilled orders at
factories; a decline in a consumer confidence survey; fewer late
deliveries of factory goods, indicating slackening demand, and
fewer new orders for consumer goods.
   Stock prices, despite the Friday-the-13th plunge in October,
were a neutral factor.
   Traditionally, three consecutive monthly declines in the leading
index are a good, but far from foolproof, indication that a
recession is on the way. It has not fallen three times in a row
this year, although it was down in May and June and flat in July.
   Berson said the overall index has probably looked worse than the
condition of the economy would warrant. It overemphasizes
manufacturing, one of the economy's weakest sectors, and
undercounts the service sector, one of the more resilient areas, he
said.
   The National Association of Purchasing Management, which tracks
the economy through a monthly survey of its members, said Friday
the manufacturing economy weakened in November for the seventh
straight month and at a faster pace than in September and October.
   In other economic news, the Office of Thrift Supervision
reported that the nation's savings and loans continue to shrink in
response to tough new financial standards taking effect next week.
Industry assets declined by $15.2 billion in September, breaking
the record of $13.3 billion set in August. Net deposit withdrawals
totaled $8.9 billion, the biggest outflow since February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891201-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 2108EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Chalk's     12-01 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chalk's,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Historic Seaplane Service to Keep Flying While Seeking Buyer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chalk's International Airlines, the nation's oldest
continuous air passenger service, will keep flying while its owner
seeks a buyer for the seaplane operation.
   Resorts International Inc. announced Thursday it will not close
the 70-year-old business on Dec. 15 as previously planned.
   Resorts, which acquired Chalk's in 1974, last month said
financial losses forced its decision to halt the airline's three
daily flights from Miami to the Bahamian island of Bimini.
   Harold Rivas, an attorney for Chalk's, said Resorts reversed its
decision following a public outcry and a plea from Bahamian
officials seeking to keep the only air service to Bimini.
   No prospective buyer has been named.
   Resorts, which is struggling under mounting debts, operates a
casino and hotel complex on Paradise Island near Nassau. Chalk's
dropped its Paradise Island route last month.
   Resorts' airline operations reported losses of $2.3 million for
the first half of 1989. The Atlantic City, N.J.-based company also
operates Paradise Island Airlines.
</TEXT>
