<DOCNO> AP891201-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1706EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     12-01 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar posted some gains Friday against
other major currencies in relatively uneventful foreign exchange
trading.
   Gold prices also rose. Republic National Bank in New York quoted
a bid for gold as of 4 p.m. EST at $413.50 a troy ounce, up $2.85
from Thursday's late bid.
   Currency traders in Europe said the dollar was helped by
profit-taking in the West German mark, which has risen steadily
against the dollar over the past month. In the United States,
analysts said many traders decided to buy dollars as a hedge
against potentially market-moving announcements from the weekend
meeting between President Bush and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
   ``The dollar traded with some strength today,'' said Craig
Sloane, financial futures analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp;
Co.
   He said the dollar got some early support from concerns about
the attempted coup in the Philippines. He said each time the dollar
weakened during the day, it managed to rebound.
   Sloane said the government's report that its leading indicators
fell 0.4 percent in October and the national purchasing manager's
survey that indicated the economy continues to decline had little
impact on the currency markets.
   ``There was nothing in those reports that wasn't anticipated by
the market,'' he said. He described currency trading as light to
moderate.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose to a closing 143.08 Japanese yen from
142.90 yen at Thursday's close. Later, in London, it slipped to
143.05 yen. In New York, the dollar rose to 143.40 yen from 142.80
yen late Thursday.
   The dollar gained ground against the British pound. In London,
the pound fell to $1.5665 from $1.5700 late Thursday. In New York,
the pound fell to $1.5625 from $1.5700 late Thursday.
   Other dollar rates in New York, compared with late rates
Thursday, included: 1.7865 West German marks, up from 1.7815;
1.5995 Swiss francs, up from 1.5930; 6.1020 French francs, up from
6.0840; 1,316.50 Italian lire, up from 1,312.25; and 1.6505
Canadian dollars, up from 1.16405.
   Selected late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates
Thursday, included: 1.7825 West German marks, up from 1.7800;
1.5925 Swiss francs, up from 1.5910; 6.0875 French francs, up from
6.0725; 2.0150 Dutch guilders, unchanged; 1,313.25 Italian lire, up
from 1,311.50; and 1.1662 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1632.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
rose $2 a troy ounce to $413.60.
   In London, gold rose to a late bid of $414.00 a troy ounce, up
from $410.60 late Thursday, while it climbed to $415.00 an ounce in
Zurich from $409.50 late Thursday. In Hong Kong, gold rose $8.39 to
$414.15 an ounce.
   Silver for current delivery slipped 0.5 cents a troy ounce to
$5.663 on New York's Comex. Earlier, silver rose in London to a
late bid of $5.70 a troy ounce, up from $5.64 late Thursday.
