<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     12-01 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rally Continues in Energy Futures Pits, Cold Weather Cited</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale home heating oil prices continued to
surge ahead Friday on buying inspired by cold weather and technical
market factors.
   Prices of other energy futures, including crude oil and unleaded
gasoline, followed heating oil higher.
   The contract for January delivery of No.2 heating oil spurted
1.10 cents to 62.91 cents a gallon on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, bringing its gain over the past two sessions to 2.87
cents. Contracts for delivery during February through April also
finished with strong increases.
   Energy analysts said traders in the heating oil pit took a cue
from enthusiastic buyers overseas, a repeat of Thursday when
strength in London spilled over into U.S. markets. The December
contract that expired Thursday jumped 2.10 cents to 62.71 cents a
gallon.
   Among other refined petroleum products traded on the New York
Merc, wholesale unleaded gasoline for January delivery rose 0.76
cent to 52.11 cents a gallon after rising 0.71 cent on Thursday.
Contracts for later delivery posted larger gains. The expired
December contract had gone up 0.57 cent to 50.29 cents a gallon on
Thursday.
   The January contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, added 41 cents to close at $20.30 per
42-gallon barrel, raising its two-day gain to 90 cents. Contracts
for delivery in February through April finished with similarly
sized increases.
   Peter Beutel, who specializes in energy for Elders Futures Inc.,
said heating oil demand has risen as temperatures have dropped.
Colder weather is occurring in the United States and in Europe.
   He said reports that low water levels on the Rhine River are
disrupting shipments and that the Soviet Union is experiencing a
shortage of heating oil sent brokers scrambling to buy futures.
   The buying begat more buying as near-month futures prices swept
past levels considered technically significant, he said. The
thresholds were 62.00 cents a gallon for the January heating oil
contract and $20.00 a barrel for January crude.
</TEXT>
