<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   12-01 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Surge On Summit Hopes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market surged Friday, lifted by a
surprise afternoon rally that drew strength from investor hopes for
lower interest rates and a promising U.S.-Soviet summit this
weekend.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 41.38 points to
2,747.65, the 10th highest close ever.
   The intensity of the rally, which sent the Dow average up more
than 50 points before it eased back, took many market observers by
surprise.
   ``I'm as shocked as anybody,'' said Brad Weeks, head of equity
trading for Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette.
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by nearly 2 to 1 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
990 issues up, 531 down and 475 unchanged.
   ``Usually markets do well prior to summits,'' said Larry
Wachtel, analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. ``I don't
know what the market expects. But there's always a gamble that
something good will come out of it.''
   A.C. Moore, director of research at Argus Research, said
investors may have been encouraged by the outlook for cuts in
government outlays for defense.
   ``These meetings could lead to an easing of the deficits that
would cause interest rates to go down,'' Moore said.
   The market also got help from economic reports that pointed to a
sluggish fourth-quarter economy. The news heightened expectations
that the Federal Reserve will cut short-term interest rates to
stimulate growth.
   The government reported that its chief economic forecasting
gauge, the Index of Leading Economic Indicators, fell 0.4 percent
in October, the sixth month of declines or no gain this year.
   That report was followed by the Purchasing Management
Association's November report showing a decline in the group's
index to 46.6 percent from 47.6 percent in October. A reading below
50 percent indicates a contraction in the nation's manufacturing
sector.
   Wall Street analysts also concluded that cash-heavy
institutional investors decided this was a good time to put their
money to work.
   A sharp rise in UAL stock helped fuel the rally in blue-chip
stocks. The stock was up 12{ to 174 on rumors that a new
employee-led buyout plan was being prepared.
   ``Institutions are looking to get out of the year with a good
performance,'' said Philip Puccio, managing director of equity
trading for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 199.20 million
shares, up from 153.20 million in the previous session.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 239.23 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market advanced $36.049 billion, or
1.07 percent, in value from Thursday.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
jumped 2.36 to 193.66.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Philip Morris rose ]
to 42}, Chevron advanced 1} to 70], General Electric added 1\ to
63\, BankAmerica gained { to 26~ and Navistar, the most active
stock, ended unchanged at 4.
   IBM, meanwhile, dropped { to 97[, Ames Department store lost 1{
to 11 and L.A. Gear fell 3 to 33.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 5.16 to 400.67, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index gained 4.64 to 350.63.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market rose
1.01 to 457.10. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 375.58, up 1.74.
</TEXT>
