<FIRST>r f AM-SEC-Finacor     12-01 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SEC-Finacor,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Extends Assets Freeze Against Finacor Anstalt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge extended a court order Friday
freezing the assets of Finacor Anstalt, a Liechtenstein company
accused by U.S. authorities of insider trading in Asea Brown Boveri
Ltd's bid for Combustion Engineering.
   In New York, U.S. District Judge John M. Cannella extended a
temporary restraining order freezing Finacor assets that the
Securities and Exchange Commission alleges may be subject to
disgorgement.
   The SEC, in a lawsuit filed earlier in New York, charged
Finacor, a financial services company, with making $2.8 million in
illegal profits allegedly using inside information about Asea Brown
Boveri's $1.6 billion bid for Combustion Engineering.
   In extending the temporary restraining order he issued last
month, Cannella ordered Finacor to account for all its assets by
next Friday.
   Cannella also ordered Finacor to return any assets transferred
out of the United States or to post a bond of equal amount.
   SEC lawyers had claimed that after they sought the asset freeze
_ but before Cannella granted it _ Finacor was liquidating some of
its assets and transferring them out of the country.
   ``Our client denies any wrongdoing,'' said John Newell, an
attorney for Finacor in New York.
   He was critical of SEC claims that a preliminary injunction was
needed because Finacor had not responded to Cannella's earlier
assets freeze order.
   ``Our clients were given notice of this action by telecopier and
overnight courier,'' said Newell, adding that his firm, Whitman and
Ransom, had ``just been retained, as of yesterday.''
   Cannella gave Finacor's lawyers until next Friday to submit
papers opposing the SEC's injunction request. A hearing is
scheduled for Dec. 20.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
