<DOCNO> AP891201-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1837EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     12-01 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Rise Moderately</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices rose moderately in cautious trading
Friday after two reports indicated the economy continues to weaken.
   The Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond rose 5-32 point, or
about $1.56 for every $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which falls
when the price rises, slipped to 7.87 percent from 7.89 percent
late Thursday.
   The biggest influence on the market was the monthly survey
issued by the National Association of Purchasing Management, which
provided evidence that business continues to slow in the
manufacturing sector, analysts said.
   The organization's Purchasing Managers Index fell a full
percentage point in November to 46.6 percent from 47.6 percent in
October.
   Robert Brusca, chief economist with Nikko Securities Co.
International Inc., said, ``The weakened index was the principal
thing that the market saw today.''
   The government's report that its chief economic forecasting
gauge, the Index of Leading Economic Indicators, fell 0.4 percent
in October also boosted bond prices.
   Both reports were seen as indications that the economy is
softening. Traders believe the Federal Reserve is more likely to
relax credit if the economy is weak. Such an action would allow
interest rates to decline and bond prices to rise.
   Ward McCarthy, a principal with Stone &amp; McCarthy Research
Associates Inc., said the market was cautious despite the economic
reports because of mixed signals from Fed in the last 10 days.
   On Monday, the Fed caught traders by surprise when it took steps
to move interest rates higher. The financial markets had expected
the central bank to ease credit.
   Traders also were wary in advance of this weekend's meeting
between President Bush and Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev,
McCarthy said, adding, ``Who knows what earth-shattering news could
come out of that?''
   In the secondary market for Treasury securities, prices of
short-term government issues rose 3-32 point, intermediate
maturities picked up 5-32 point and long-term issues rose 5-32
point to 7-32 point, according to figures provided by Telerate
Inc., a financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, rose 2.21 to 1,196.49.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 7.76 percent as the
discount dropped 8 basis points to 7.52 percent. Yields on
six-month bills declined to 7.72 percent as the discount fell 5
basis points to 7.34 percent. Yields on one-year bills slipped to
7.64 percent as the discount lost 5 basis points to 7.14 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds rose 15-32 point to 93 13-16. The average
yield to maturity fell to 7.23 percent from 7.24 percent late
Thursday.
   The federal funds rate, the interest charge on short-term loans
between banks, was quoted at 8 7-16 percent, down from 8| percent
late Thursday.
</TEXT>
