<DOCNO> AP891201-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 1915EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-01 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Surging Heating-Oil Demand Drives Energy Futures Higher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices rose sharply Friday on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, paced by a surging heating-oil market that
jumped more than 5 percent in the week's last three trading days.
   On other commodity markets Friday, corn and soybean prices fell
while wheat futures were mixed, gold rose, silver fell, cattle
futures advanced and pork futures were mixed.
   Heating oil futures settled .57 cent to 1.32 cents higher in New
York with the contract for delivery in January up 1.10 cents at
62.91 cents a gallon.
   Crude oil finished 37 cents to 44 cents higher with January at
$20.30 a barrel; unleaded gasoline was .65 cent to 1.01 cents
higher with January at 52.11 cents a gallon.
   Heating-oil futures have been climbing since August and have
risen faster with the onset of cold weather, reflecting unusually
tight supplies both in the United States and in Europe.
   The European supply situation is more severe, a result of
disruptions in the movement of heating oil from the Soviet Union, a
major European supplier, and the low level of the Rhine River,
which has further restricted the movement of supplies.
   Meanwhile, early episodes of cold weather in the United States
and in Europe have stirred strong demand for heating oil.
   ``We've had a good, quick start to the winter and we're having
heating oil usage at a very high level,'' said Ray Mazzeo, an
energy futures specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The strength in heating oil has more than offset the bearish
punch of OPEC's agreement to raise its crude-oil production ceiling
to 22 million barrels a day from 20.5 million barrels in the first
half of 1990.
   ``If not for heating oil coming to the rescue there the last
couple days, crude oil could very easily be a dollar lower right
now,'' said James Ritterbusch, vice president of trading and
research at Carson Petroleum Co., a Chicago-area oil distributor.
   Corn and soybean futures fell substantially on the Chicago Board
of Trade in a late, technically inspired drop.
   Wheat futures finished mixed, supported by rumors that the
Soviet Union had bid for 400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at
subsidized prices.
   Talk of increased Soviet purchases of U.S. grain has dominated
trading ahead of this weekend's meeting between President Bush and
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
   After the close, the USDA announced sales of 800,000 tons of
corn and 100,000 tons of soybean meal to the Soviets, partially
confirming rumors that had supported those markets on Thursday.
   Wheat futures settled 1\ cents lower to } cent higher with
December at $4.08\ a bushel; corn was { cent to 3} cents lower with
December at $2.34{ a bushel; oats were { cent to 1{ cents lower
with December at $1.43} a bushel; soybeans were 2\ cents to 6{
cents lower with January at $5.76\ a bushel.
   Gold futures rose modestly on New York's Commodity Exchange in
quiet trading. Silver finished slightly lower.
   Gold settled $1.80 to $2 higher with December at $413.60 a troy
ounce; silver was 0.1 cent to 0.7 cent lower with December at
$5.663 a troy ounce.
   Frozen pork belly futures fell for the fifth straight day on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange, although not as sharply as in the
three previous sessions. The market has collapsed amid
disappointment over the slow pace at which the government is buying
pork bellies to donate to Poland.
   Hog futures closed mixed while cattle futures advanced in a
technical correction after falling along with the belly market for
most of the week.
   Live cattle futures settled .05 cent to .35 cent higher with
December at 75.20 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to
.23 cent higher with January at 82.85 cents a pound; live hogs were
.30 cent lower to .37 cent higher with December at 50.55 cents a
pound; frozen pork bellies were .05 cent to 1.05 cents lower with
February at 57.50 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
