<DOCNO> AP891201-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 2006EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BusinessHighlights     12-01 0839</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0882</SECOND>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street leaders declared an end to
their lengthy battle to keep banks out of the stocks and bonds
business, proposing to junk the law that has governed the nation's
basic banking structure since the Depression.
   Directors of the Securities Industry Association, at the trade
group's annual convention, on Friday endorsed a proposal for new
legislation to let subsidiaries of banks ``engage in a broad range
of securities and securities-related activities.''
   At the same time, the SIA said its plan would let brokers engage
in consumer banking businesses and join banks in having access to
the Federal Reserve's banking system.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's chief economic forecasting
gauge signaled a slowdown in October, but other evidence suggested
that lower interest rates will keep the economy from toppling into
a recession.
   The 0.4 percent drop in the Commerce Department's Index of
Leading Economic Indicators reported Friday fits in with the
consensus among analysts that the final quarter of this year and
the first three months of 1990 will see weak growth at best.
   However, some analysts said a number of factors mitigated the
unfavorable report.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The manufacturing sector provided further
evidence of a weakening economy as purchasing executives reported
that business slowed again in November at the nation's industrial
companies.
   The National Association of Purchasing Management, which charts
economic trends with a monthly survey of purchasing executives,
said Friday the economy deteriorated for the seventh straight month
as production levels declined for the fifth straight month.
   The organization's Purchasing Managers Index fell to 46.6
percent from 47.6 in October.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first gain in single-family home building
in nine months helped boost construction spending in October, the
government said in a report suggesting lower interest rates are
helping end a construction slump.
   The Commerce Department said Friday that spending rose 1 percent
to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $420.1 billion.
   The increase followed no change in September and a 1.5 percent
gain in August. Construction spending fell in July and June.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's thrift institutions continued to
shrink dramatically in September in preparation for tough new
financial standards taking effect the coming week, the government
said.
   Assets at the nation's 2,903 thrifts shrank by $15.2 billion,
breaking the record set in August of $13.3 billion, the Office of
Thrift Supervision said Friday.
   Meanwhile, a net of $8.9 billion in deposits was withdrawn from
thrifts, the most since February, which marked the second-heaviest
outflow on record. September was the 16th consecutive month of
outflows.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The merchant shipping industry said President
Bush's decision to bar Panamanian-flag vessels from U.S. ports
could make shipowners pawns in diplomatic disputes.
   The move might interrupt free trade and prove costly and
disruptive to shipowners, industry insiders said Friday.
   Bush's ban, announced Thursday, goes into effect Jan. 31 and is
one of various U.S. economic sanctions already in place against
Panama's leader, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PacifiCorp offered to acquire Pinnacle
West Capital Corp., three weeks after proposing a buyout of the
company's Arizona Public Service Co., its only profitable division.
   PacifiCorp, which has interests in electric utilities in seven
Western states, made its offer Friday contingent on the sale of
MeraBank, Pinnacle West's troubled savings bank subsidiary.
   PacifiCorp offered to exchange 0.18 of a share of its own stock
for each outstanding Pinnacle West share. Based on PacifiCorp's
current stock price the offer has an indicated value of nearly $8 a
share, or a total of about $693.7 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private exporting companies have sold the
Soviet Union an additional 800,000 metric tons of U.S. corn for
delivery in 1989-90 under a long-term supply agreement, the
Agriculture Department said.
   The department said Friday that 100,000 tons of soybean meal
also were sold to the Soviet Union for 1989-90 delivery.
   Orders since Oct. 1, the beginning of the agreement's new year,
now total about 10.3 million tons of corn, 160,700 tons of
soybeans, 705,000 tons of soybean meal and 7,100 tons of barley.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For sale: Used 12-wheel truck, with trailer. Army
green. Maximum speed 25 mph. Weight 62,000 pounds. Previously used
only for hauling nuclear missiles.
   That was one of the offerings Friday at an unusual Red Tag Sale
put on by the Soviet Ministry of Defense and several semi-public
organizations to recoup some of the cold cash spent in the Cold War.
   The sale items were military support equipment for the
medium-range nuclear missiles destroyed under a 1987 U.S.-Soviet
agreement.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associted Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market surged Friday, as the Dow Jones average of 30
industrials jumped 41.38 points to 2,747.65, the 10th highest close
ever.
   Bond prices rose moderately.
   The dollar advanced against other major currencies.
   Oil futures prices rose sharply; corn and soybean prices fell;
wheat futures were mixed, gold rose while silver fell; cattle
futures advanced and pork futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
